r the bills are paid. Sometimes I have to dip into savings to get through the week! So PLEASE TAKE THE MONEY out NOW!',0,'2012-03-24 17:23:07','2012-03-24 17:23:07'),(384,357,'Newsletter Signup From New Account',0,'2012-03-24 17:40:14','2012-03-24 17:40:14'),(385,358,'Newsletter Signup From New Account',0,'2012-03-25 01:18:35','2012-03-25 01:18:35'),(386,358,'We have not received a receipt or record of our monetary contributions for 2011.  Please respond with questions or explanation as soon as possible.  Thank you!',0,'2012-03-25 01:22:01','2012-03-25 01:22:01'),(387,359,'Dear CAM,\r\nI am an RN and a certified nurse-midwife (CNM)from Oregon. This past week I was contacted by a group of midwives and asked if I would be interested in working at a clinic in Caphaitian, Haiti that has been started by a group of midwives since the earthquake. \r\n\r\nI know that CAM, as well as some other Mennonite groups, have mission base(s) in Haiti. I am wondering if CAM could tell me where the CAM clinic is in relation to Caphaitian (not sure if I am spelling it right.) and/or put me in  contact with their mission personnel in Haiti. \r\n\r\nGod bless!\r\nMary ',0,'2012-03-25 03:34:15','2012-03-25 03:34:15'),(388,360,'Reach out ministries seek to transform religious bodies in the face of the HIV/AIDS crisis, in order that they may become a force for transformation – that is bringing healing, hope and accompaniment to all affected by HIV/AIDS. Reach out ministries began addressing HIV/AIDS in 2006 by incorporating HIV prevention education into reproductive health programs in Malawi. Since then, the HIV/AIDS program at  has expanded into 4 countries worldwide(Malawi, Zambia, South Africa and Ghana) and provides a full spectrum of prevention, care, treatment, and support. \r\n\r\nPrevention, HIV risk reduction, and voluntary counseling and testing expansion are mainstays of reach out ministries’ approach to HIV prevention. Program approaches range from HIV orphan support , prevention for in-school youth , prevention for street youth, rapid voluntary counseling and testing scale-up and clinics, mobile and border populations, injection drug users and pregnant women, including prevention of mother to child transmission. \r\n\r\nOur broad areas of expertise and experience in care and support for people living with HIV includes antiretroviral therapy (ART) scale up and capacity building, care and support for people living with HIV at the family and community level, stigma reduction, and technical assistance to governments, health ministries, and partner non-governmental organizations. \r\n\r\nReach out ministries prides itself on developed quality and sustainable HIV/AIDS prevention, care, and treatment education programs and leading innovative programs to address cutting edge problems in HIV and related infectious diseases. Recent examples include HIV/TB co-infection, and orphan support programs combining income generation programs with health education. \r\n\r\nAmong reach out ministries’ recent accomplishments in the area of HIV/AIDS:8,759 health care workers have been trained and 14,655 students and general community members have been educated about HIV care and prevention. Peer educators reached nearly 400,000 people in a cross border project in Malawi \r\n\r\n An HIV/AIDS Prevention Education is accessed by more than 15,000 community members, mostly at-risk youth, and has trained more than 500 professionals. \r\n\r\nYouth participated in abstinence and being faithful behavior change activities, while gaining valuable life skills experience \r\n\r\nIn the first year 3 years of our program, 4,128 orphans and 1,127 guardians received support and training in our orphan program both in Malawi, Zambia, South Africa and Ghana. \r\n\r\nReach out ministries has targeted to work with the church communities for the following reasons: \r\n\r\n•         The people that are infected and affected are members of the church, therefore it is the responsibility of the church to become a community that projects good values and a beacon of hope to those infected and affected by HIV/AIDS. \r\n\r\n•         The church has to be at the forefront in the fight against HIV/AIDS. \r\n\r\n•         The church is equipped with God’s armour and other spiritual weapons with which to challenge sin and wickedness on earth \r\n\r\n•         The church has a long history of presence, proclamation and persuasion. \r\n\r\n•         Have a well- developed structure. \r\n\r\n•         Are self- sustaining. \r\n\r\n•         Have a captive loyal audience which meets every week. \r\n\r\n•         Have predictable leadership. \r\n\r\n•         Have grassroots support and understand the language at the grassroots level. \r\n\r\n•         The church gives hope beyond the grave. \r\n\r\n•         Have the scripture manual with tested and proven effectiveness in changing behavior morals. \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nContact us;\r\n\r\nJones Chamangwana\r\nExecutive Director\r\nThe Registered trustees of Reach out ministries\r\nP.O BOX 544\r\nBALAKA\r\nMALAWI\r\nMobile;(265) 888 872 254\r\nE-mail; reachoutmalawi@gmail.com\r\nministeringsouls@yahoo.co.uk\r\n\r\n',0,'2012-03-25 08:40:55','2012-03-25 08:40:55'),(389,361,'Newsletter Signup Form Submittal',0,'2012-03-26 08:56:13','2012-03-26 08:56:13'),(390,362,'Hello.  We had my brother-in-law, Dwayne Stoltzfus, ask if CAM can use hospital gowns we had available to us for your clinics.  You said you wanted 500 of them; Dwayne plans to take them to the CAM warehouse in Berlin tomorrow.  We would like a receipt sent to us for tax deduction purposes.  We understand that you send a blank receipt (as far as the value of the donation is concerned ) & we fill in that amount ourselves.  Is that correct?',0,'2012-03-27 00:41:22','2012-03-27 00:41:22'),(391,363,'Newsletter Signup From New Account',0,'2012-03-27 13:20:43','2012-03-27 13:20:43'),(392,364,'Newsletter Signup From New Account',0,'2012-03-27 20:04:56','2012-03-27 2