INSERT INTO `news_item_translations` VALUES (13,13,'en','Open House 2011','<p>We invite you to join us at Christian Aid Ministries\' twenty-sixth annual Open House on November 4 &amp; 5, 2011. CAM staff members will share firsthand reports, experiences, and slides about the work they are involved in. Get a glimpse of how your donations, prayers, and volunteer work are blessing thousands of people around the globe.</p>\r\n<h3>Location: Christian Aid Ministries warehouse, 2412 Division Highway, Ephrata, Pennsylvania</h3>\r\n<iframe marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&amp;source=s_q&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=2412+Division+Highway,+Ephrata,+Pennsylvania&amp;aq=&amp;sll=37.0625,-95.677068&amp;sspn=55.323926,135.263672&amp;vpsrc=0&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=2412+Division+Hwy,+Ephrata,+Pennsylvania+17522&amp;t=m&amp;ll=40.141615,-76.105986&amp;spn=0.019684,0.025749&amp;z=14&amp;iwloc=A&amp;output=embed\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"450\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\"></iframe>\r\n<small><a href=\"http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&amp;source=embed&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=2412+Division+Highway,+Ephrata,+Pennsylvania&amp;aq=&amp;sll=37.0625,-95.677068&amp;sspn=55.323926,135.263672&amp;vpsrc=0&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=2412+Division+Hwy,+Ephrata,+Pennsylvania+17522&amp;t=m&amp;ll=40.141615,-76.105986&amp;spn=0.019684,0.025749&amp;z=14&amp;iwloc=A\" style=\"color:#0000FF;text-align:left\">View Larger Map</a>\r\n</small>\r\n<h3>Area airports close to CAM</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Harrisburg	- 45 minutes from CAM</li>\r\n<li>Philadelphia	- 1 hour &amp; 15 minutes from CAM</li>\r\n<li>Baltimore	- 2 hours from CAM</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h1>Schedule of Activities</h1>\r\n<h2>Evening Slide Presentation</h2>\r\n<h3>November 4 &amp; 5 - Friday &amp; Saturday evening</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">The same slides will be shown both evenings. There should be plenty of room for everyone.</p>\r\n<h3>7:00-9:00	Slides about CAM programs</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Trail of a food parcel - Paul A. Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>A priceless hope - <em>Support-A-Widow</em> - Seth Martin, Alabama (former Liberia staff)</li>\r\n<li>Boxes of blessings - <em>Nicaragua-Adopt-A-Family</em>	- Kevin Steiner, Nicaragua</li>\r\n<li>Manna from our Heavenly Father - <em>Adopt-A-Family</em>	- Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>Help for Romania’s elderly	- Matthew Bontrager, Illinois (former Romania staff)</li>\r\n<li>“God’s eyes are on us” - Hope-for-the-Handicapped	- Seth Martin, Alabama (former Liberia staff)</li>\r\n<li>Bibles for the bush people in Liberia - <em>Bibles-for-the-World</em> - Paul Hershberger, Colorado</li>\r\n<li>Sharing Christ’s love in the land of the Bible	- Daniel Miller, Virginia (former Israel staff)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Children’s story time with Johnny Miller</h3>\r\n<ul><li>“And the Gentiles shall come to thy light . . . ” Isaiah 60:3 - <em>Jericho Road Ministries, Sponsor-A-Bible-Lesson, and Nathaniel Orphanage update</em>	Titus Miller, Romania</li>\r\n<li>Pointing America to Christ - <em>Billboard Evangelism</em>	Dwayne Stoltzfus, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>Rapid Response Teams/Disaster Response Services	- Willie Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>Tribulation, distress, persecution, and famine - <em>International Crisis Projects</em>	- David Leid, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>A dollars’ worth of health and life - <em>Gifts-That-Grow, Medicines-for-Multitudes</em>	- Kevin Steiner, Nicaragua</li>\r\n<li>Save-A-Life!	Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>Clothing blessings from afar - <em>Clothing Bundle Project</em>	- Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>Touching the lives of the fatherless - <em>Support-an-Orphan</em>	- Merle Beachy, Kenya</li>\r\n<li>Haiti-Sponsor-A-Child school program	- Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>Potential for Liberia’s farmers - <em>Seed Project</em>	- Seth Martin, Alabama (former Liberia staff)</li>\r\n<li>Working with our hands - <em>Family-Self-Support</em>	Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>Hope &amp; Opportunity - one family at a time - <em>SALT Microfinance Solutions</em>	Harold Herr, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>Value of volunteers	- Paul A. Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>Liberia, through the eyes of a child	- Elvin Stoltzfus, Liberia (not present, voice recording)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Daytime Schedule</h2>\r\n<h3>November 5 - Saturday daytime session</h3>\r\n<ul><li>7:45-9:45	Biblical Stewardship Seminar	- Paul A. Miller</li>\r\n<li>8:30-9:45	Self-guided tours of warehouse and cannery</li>\r\n<li>10:00	Singing and devotional meditation</li>\r\n<li>10:30	Manna from our Heavenly Father - <em>Adopt-A-Family</em>	- Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>10:40	Special-Needs-Fund - Seth Martin, Alabama (former Liberia staff)</li>\r\n<li>10:50	Save-A-Life!	- Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>11:05	Touching the lives of the fatherless - <em>Support-an-Orphan</em>	- Merle Beachy, Kenya</li>\r\n<li>11:20	Boxes of blessings - <em>Nicaragua-Adopt-A-Family</em>	- Kevin Steiner, Nicaragua</li>\r\n<li>11:30	Haiti-Sponsor-A-Child school program	- Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>11:40	CAM update and inform	- David Troyer, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>12:00	Lunch <em>Please bring finger foods, etc. - especially sandwiches. Thank you! Beverages will be provided. Free time to browse warehouse, displays, and book tables. Take advantage of the Open 	House special: 25% off all CAM-published books and CDs.</em>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>1:40	“And the Gentiles shall come to thy light . . . ” Isaiah 60:3 - <em>Jericho Road Ministries,        			Sponsor-A-Bible-Lesson, and Nathaniel Orphanage</em> <em>update</em>	- Titus Miller, Romania</li>\r\n<li>1:50	Hope &amp; Opportunity - one family at a time - <em>SALT Microfinance Solutions</em>	- Gary Miller, Idaho&#160;</li>\r\n<li>2:05	Rapid Response Teams/Disaster Response Services -	Paul Weaver, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>2:20	Biblical Stewardship Services	- Paul A. Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>2:25	Working with our hands - <em>Family-Self-Support</em>	- Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>2:35	Help for Romania’s elderly	- Matthew Bontrager, Illinois (former Romania staff)</li>\r\n<li>2:45	Sharing Christ’s love in the land of the Bible -	Daniel Miller, Virginia (former Israel staff)</li>\r\n<li>2:55	Pointing America to Christ - <em>Billboard Evangelism</em>	Johnny Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,'2011-10-13 17:23:07','2011-10-19 15:36:53'),(8,8,'en','A Ray of Hope in Their Final Years','<p>Juan and Cruz live with their crippled son Isidro in a small house beside the church where they are members. In exchange for rent, they clean the church and maintain its premises. Their only income is the $25 their children give them each month and the $10 cash they receive with their food parcel from CAM. They use the cash to buy medicines for Isidro and more food. <br />Life is difficult for elderly people in Nicaragua. Healthcare for the elderly is free, but the hospitals are unsanitary and usually do not have the proper equipment or medicines. When older people develop major health problems they often die for lack of quality treatment. These people depend on their children or extended family to survive. <br />\"Their helplessness and dependence on others are the biggest things that stand out to me,\" says Andy Yoder, CAM\'s distribution director in Nicaragua. \"Some die simply for lack of basic necessities.\"</p>\r\n<h2>Hope in Haiti</h2>\r\n<p>Madam Belia sits on the steps of her hurricane-damaged, tarp-covered house. Sunshine and strong winds have weathered the tarp. When it rains at night, she covers herself with a piece of plastic to stay dry. Nevertheless she pleasantly states, \"God is good to me. Everything in the box is so helpful. I keep you on my mind in prayer. Thank you, thank you for the food.\"</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Madam Belia is another recipient of CAM\'s <strong><a title=\"Help-for-the-Elderly\" href=\"/programs/14\">Help-for-the-Elderly (HFTE)</a> </strong>program. These older people suffer so much yet deeply appreciate the help they receive from sponsors.\r\n</p>\r\n<p><strong><a title=\"Help-for-the-Elderly\" href=\"/programs/14\">HFTE</a>\r\n</strong> recipients receive a parcel every month. Pastors from evangelical churches give us names of the poorest in their churches. CAM staff visits these families, and if they are within CAM\'s policy to receive a parcel, we add them to the program. After they are added to the list, they receive a monthly parcel until their situation improves and someone poorer needs a parcel.</p>\r\n<p>Many older people who are Christians portray a strong faith in God that He will provide for them. Many times they view the help they receive from CAM as a direct answer to their prayer for help.</p>\r\n<p>For Juan and his family, Madam Belia, and hundreds more elderly people, a monthly food parcel is a bright ray of hope in their life and more times than not, the only way they survive.</p>\r\n',NULL,'2011-09-02 20:27:40','2011-10-27 14:49:59'),(14,14,'en','On the Road  to Healing','<p>Deep potholes dot the narrow road leading to the clinic. No yellow lines run down the middle or white lines along its side, just a winding “lane” between miles of dense jungle forest. But the quality of the road is of least importance to the little girl with her foot wrapped in a dirty bandage. Or to Nyato Malu, a young man with “falling down sickness” as the Liberians call epilepsy. They are on the road that leads to a source of healing. </p>\r\n<p>Zeewhorr Community Clinic, nestled in a little town in the bush of Liberia, is a place where healing can be found. Dr. Gharweah Toe, the highest medically educated man for miles around, is a licensed physician’s assistant and the only “doctor” for hundreds of people in the area. Thanks to generous donors, Dr. Toe has fresh bandages and treatment for the little girl with the snakebite on her foot and medicine for Nyato. </p>\r\n<p>Sometimes the seizures would come on Nyato every five minutes. His mother struggled to care for her son, and her friends told her to take him to the witch doctor, but she refused. When she heard the clinic at Zeewhorr had medicine for this kind of sickness, she brought her son an hour’s walk to the clinic and is now pleased with the results. She says, “It can be fine when he on the medicines.” </p>\r\n<p>CAM supporters supply donated medicines and medical supplies to this clinic and hundreds of others throughout Liberia, Romania, El Salvador, Nicaragua, and Haiti. For most of these clinics, it’s the only way they can keep their facilities open. With God’s help and your support, people in need are on the road to healing.</p>',NULL,'2011-10-27 18:33:20','2011-10-27 18:33:20'),(9,9,'en','Light and Truth in Monrovia\'s Prison Halls','<p>Bright sunlight filters through the iron bars of the cell window, offering a false hope to the detainees inside. Cold and dark, the cell seems to snatch away any glimmer of hope and replace it with depression and stress.  Not knowing when or if they will return to civilization, the inmates have little left to live for. Unfortunately, this is life for most prisoners in Liberia.</p>\r\n<p>But some of the inmates in Monrovia, Liberia, experience something different. The cold, iron bars no longer discourage them.  Stress and depression no longer reign in the prison halls. These men have found faith in Jesus Christ, the Light and Truth of all!</p>\r\n<p>Several years ago, Light Mennonite Church in Liberia began to distribute Bible correspondence courses in prisons throughout Monrovia. These courses are published by Lamp and Light and funded by CAM\'s <strong><a title=\"News\" href=\"/programs/35\">Sponsor-A-Bible-Lesson</a>\r\n</strong> program. Inmates declare the courses to be the \"liberator of their lost souls.\" Brother Sayon, Lamp and Light office assistant, reports, \"The courses have trained up pastors, evangelists, and praying brethren within the prison . . . \"</p>\r\n<p>New believers testify the courses strengthen their faith in God. They are thankful for the knowledge they gain from their studies, and that they no longer need to be among the ignorant ones who are being destroyed (Hosea 4:6). Their daily prayer is that they will not stray from the Truth they have received.</p>\r\n<p>Thank you, supporters, for making it possible to provide Bible lessons for lost and struggling inmates in Liberia! Please pray the inmates in the dreaded prisons of Monrovia would continue walking in Truth even after they are released from prison.</p>',NULL,'2011-09-02 20:41:49','2011-10-25 13:16:39'),(10,10,'en','Bibles to the Bush','<p>Liberia is a land of darkness, but many people also have a real hunger for the Word of God. This year again, God led a small team from America to bring several thousand Bibles and Christian literature to the bush parts of Liberia where some people had never owned a Bible. Pray the Gospel message will take root in these villages where spiritual darkness and superstition abound.</p>',NULL,'2011-09-06 12:33:13','2011-10-05 19:02:51'),(11,11,'en','My Mother Does Not Know','<p style=\"font-style: italic;\"><strong>Children\'s Corner</strong> - The true story of Rose Toe, a sponsored girl at the Peter Sayklon orphanage in Kakata, Liberia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\"My mother does not know,<br />My mother does not know,<br />My mother does not know,<br />I will let her know.\"</p>\r\n<p>I just learned this song. I learned it in February when I came to live at the Peter Sayklon orphanage in Kakata. The song means my mother does not know about Jesus. There are more verses . . . \"My father does not know, my brother does not know, my sister does not know, my people do not know.\"</p>\r\n<p>It used to be true of me. I didn\'t know about Jesus. But now I am learning about Him, and I love Him. I know He is coming again to take us home to heaven. We sing more verses to the song:&#160;</p>\r\n<p>\"Yes, I love the Lord,       <br />Yes, I love the Lord,<br />Yes, I love the Lord,<br />Down in my heart.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"He is coming again,<br />He is coming again,<br />He is coming again, <br />On judgment day.\" </p>\r\n<p>I learn many other songs at my new home. I love to sing the song, \"When We All Get to Heaven.\" After we sing this song, my orphanage mother says to us children, \"I always ask you one question, and every day I will ask you that question. You can sing so much. But are you going to sing in heaven? You sure you will be there?\"<br />We always answer, \"Yes!\" I make sure my voice is heard when I answer, \"Yes, I will be there in heaven!\"<br />Here at the orphanage, I have plenty of rice to eat and soon I will get my own notebook and pencil and go to school. My sponsor in America sends money to CAM every month and that pays for everything I need. I tell God and my sponsor, \"thank you!\"<br />I now know about Jesus. But my mother still does not know. And my people in River Gee do not know about Jesus. My orphanage mother prays with me that someday, someday soon, the people in my area will learn about Jesus. River Gee is far away, and we can\'t easily go there. But we pray someone will take them the message, and they can hear about Jesus. Just like I learned about Jesus at the orphanage.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">In southeastern Liberia, tradition has it that when a woman\'s husband dies, she is forced to marry his brother or another man within his family to carry on the family line. Sometimes the woman runs away to avoid marrying a man she does not love. After Rose\'s father died, her mother ran away so she would not be forced into marrying. Rose and her brothers Terry and David were left alone. <br />Martha Sayklon, director of the Peter Sayklon orphanage, heard of their sad story, had compassion on them, and brought them to her orphanage. Please pray for Rose and her brothers. At the orphanage, they receive love, care, and Bible teaching. Pray they will continue to feel God\'s love touch their hearts and stay safe and secure. <br />Pray also for the many people in River Gee and other parts of Africa who do not know about Jesus. Pray that someone would carry to them the message of God, His love, and His soon return.</p>',NULL,'2011-09-07 13:20:25','2011-10-14 20:10:57'),(12,12,'en','From Starving to Satisfied','<p>Baby Tee\'s face was once contorted by severe malnutrition and suffering. His mother was sick in the hospital, his father had abandoned him, and Baby Tee was left in the care of his grandmother. When his grandmother brought him to the CAM office in Liberia, our staff gave them two cans of infant formula. Two weeks later, when the staff visited them, Baby Tee was wearing an expression of utter contentment as he downed another bottle of the formula that helped save his life.</p>\r\n<p>Around the world, children suffer from neglect and undernourishment. Some make a full recovery, others do not. Thanks to God and faithful supporters, hundreds of cans of infant formula and nutritional drink mix find their way to remote corners of Liberia, Haiti, or Nicaragua where they help save other precious lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"Baby Tee, after infant formula\" title=\"Baby Tee, After Infant Formula\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIvMjAxMS8wOS8wNy8wOV81Nl8xMl80MjVfQmFieV9UZWVfQWZ0ZXIuSlBHBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg00NTB4NDUwPgY7BlQ/Baby_Tee_After.JPG\" height=\"299\" width=\"450\" /></p>',NULL,'2011-09-07 13:56:53','2011-10-26 13:58:01'),(15,15,'en','Radiating Warmth to Hands and Hearts','<p>From the first chilly wind of October until the early weeks of May, gas and wood stoves radiate their warmth into Ukrainian homes. But buying firewood and gas quickly takes a heavy toll on the typical Ukrainian household. The average expense during one winter season is $425, a serious strain on meager incomes. A few fortunate families are able to harvest firewood on their own property. But many families, to lower heating bills, resort to heating only a portion or one room of their house. Lack of warmth is especially hard on the health of young children and the elderly and ailing.</p>\r\n<p>To help ease the hardships brought on by the long, bitter winters, CAM operates the <strong><a title=\"Warm-A-Family\" href=\"/programs/29\">Warm-A-Family</a>\r\n</strong> (WAF) program in Ukraine, Romania, and Moldova. Money to pay heating bills is distributed through pastors, who give us the names of the neediest families in their churches. In 2010, CAM was able to give funds to 778 churches, totaling 2,908 recipient families. </p>\r\n<p>One recipient of the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"Warm-A-Family\" href=\"/programs/29\">WAF</a> program in Ukraine is Vala Condrasiva. Her husband left her eighteen years ago, and she has to provide for the needs of her three children on her own. She has an income of $105 per month if she can find work cleaning houses. Vala has multiple medical problems that need attention and her oldest daughter now has cancer. Vala ignores her own medical  problems to provide for the treatment her oldest daughter needs. Her youngest daughter has an eye disease that is not curable but is stabilized with expensive treatment. </p>\r\n<p>Vala received <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"Warm-A-Family\" href=\"/programs/29\">WAF</a> funds to pay for wood to heat her small house, which used to be a barn. She says, “<strong><a title=\"/programs/30\" href=\"/programs/30\">Warm-A-Family</a>\r\n</strong> funds have made a real difference in my life; without it, it would have been very difficult to provide for my family.”</p>\r\n<p>Sister Raisa, another Ukrainian, probably echoes many other recipients’ responses: <em>“I thank you, my dear brothers and sisters in Christ, from the bottom of my heart for the help received in buying firewood for heating my house. This past winter was especially cold and hard, and my pension is small. I hardly have money for food and medicines. May the Lord reward you hundredfold!”</em>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>The <strong><a title=\"/programs/30\" href=\"/programs/30\">Warm-A-Family</a>\r\n</strong> program not only blesses needy recipients; it also rewards the distributors. Here is a word from Dean Wengerd, CAM’s Ukraine field director: “The Bible says in Proverbs 14:21, <em>Happy is the man that considers the poor.</em> It brings great joy to my heart to be involved in helping people like Vala find solutions to hard situations. I consider it a privilege to be a part of helping people who need assistance like this.”</p>',NULL,'2011-10-27 18:44:31','2011-10-27 18:47:09'),(16,16,'en','Hope for Needy Widows','<p>“What will I make for our next meal?” “When will we eat again?” “How can I buy more charcoal so I can cook?”</p>\r\n<p>Imagine asking these questions and finding yourself in a situation with no money, no food, and almost no hope. For needy widows in Haiti, Nicaragua, Liberia, Israel, and other countries, the <strong><a title=\"/programs/28\" href=\"/programs/28\">Support-A-Widow</a>\r\n</strong> food parcels give hope to widows whose lives are clouded with poverty and uncertainty. </p>\r\n<p>Fifty-year-old Marie Denisse in Haiti has six children, but she was never married to their father. Since his death, she became a believer and decided to remain single and raise her children on her own. Their home was destroyed in the earthquake, but God has blessed them with a new home. </p>\r\n<p>She says, “The food box brings much relief to the load of caring for six children. I pray much for those who send the box. I didn’t have anything, but now God has blessed me.” </p>\r\n<p>But he saveth the poor from the hand of the mighty...so the poor hath hope.\" Job 5:15-16a</p>',NULL,'2011-10-27 18:54:45','2011-10-27 18:59:42'),(17,17,'en','Spreading the Truth from North to South','<p><em>I pull my warm fur-lined coat closer as the strong wind whips around me. I, a Nenet tribal member from the Yamal Peninsula in northwest Siberia, Russia, peer off into the distance, noting the barren tundra landscape; no trees, few plants, and flat plains for many miles. As I shield my eyes from the bright sun, I notice a group of men struggling against the wind to make it to shelter. They slowly make it to our campsite, so I welcome them out of the cold and into our reindeer skin tent. Worried the weary travelers may be famished from their journey, I give them food and drink. They show their gratitude with a smile, and bring out a suitcase full of literature. They hand me</em> The Seed of Truth <em>magazine. I feel new joy and hope as I read through the magazine and discover the Gospel. </em>\r\n</p><p>The Nenets of northwest Siberia, Russia, are not the only ones overjoyed with Christian literature. Believers in many countries are blessed and encouraged by the things they read in CAM Christian family magazines. An eleven-year old girl from Poland requested to have her own copies of <em>The Seed of Truth</em>. She says, “Such beautiful things are written for children, about birds, animals, and other interesting things. I love to read it.” In Moldova, the Vanya Muntean family, who saves the magazines to reread in the future, is deeply encouraged by the articles. On the other side of the globe, Christians’ lives in South America have been changed through <em>The Torch of Truth</em> magazines, “There are many good testimonies to tell on the enormous blessings the “Torch” has caused in so many lives, homes, and cities of our nation . . .” writes a pastor from Nicaragua.</p>\r\n<p>Through the prayers and donations of supporters like you, many lives have been changed throughout the world! Please pray for those whose lives may be touched through these magazines. </p>',NULL,'2011-10-27 19:06:28','2011-10-27 19:06:28'),(18,18,'en','Billboard Evangelism','<p>More than a year ago, a young Jewish girl seeking for truth, called the toll-free number on a CAM billboard and talked with one of our tele-counselors. Recently she called again and left a message, thanking him for the seed he had planted in her heart and praising God that she has received Jesus as her “Messiah” and Savior! </p>\r\n<p>CAM’s <a title=\"Billboard Evangelism\" href=\"/programs/6\"><strong>Billboard Evangelism</strong>\r\n</a> program has more than one hundred Gospel messages posted in all fifty states. You can find out more about what God is doing through these Gospel messages by reading the quarterly Billboard Evangelism newsletter. (To sign up call 330-893-4888).</p>',NULL,'2011-10-27 19:09:18','2011-10-27 19:09:18'),(19,19,'en','Disaster Response Services','<p>The same way a bridge spans the gap between two mountains, volunteers through CAM’s <strong><a title=\"/programs/11\" href=\"/programs/11\">Disaster Response Services</a>\r\n\r\n</strong> span the gap between disaster and recovery for victims of a tornado, flood, hurricane, or other natural disaster.</p>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<p><img src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSImMjAxMS8xMC8yNy8yM18yN18yNF85OTdfZHJzXzEuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg0yMjV4MjU1PgY7BlQ/drs_1.jpg\" height=\"225\" width=\"225\" />\r\n<img style=\"width: 196px; height: 225px;\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIlMjAxMS8xMC8yNy8yM18yN18yNV84M19kcnNfMi5qcGcGOgZFVFsIOgZwOgp0aHVtYkkiDTIyNXgyNTU+BjsGVA/drs_2.jpg\" />\r\n<img style=\"width: 150px; height: 225px;\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSImMjAxMS8xMC8yNy8yM18yN18yNV8yNjhfZHJzXzMuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg0yMjV4MjU1PgY7BlQ/drs_3.jpg\" /></p>',NULL,'2011-10-27 19:31:13','2011-10-27 19:42:18'),(20,20,'en','Special-Needs-Fund','<p>Ten-year-old Nathan in Liberia was hit in the eye with a piece of rock. The eye was severely damaged and needed to be removed. His family didn’t have enough money for a prosthetic eye, but thanks to the <a title=\"/programs/26\" href=\"/programs/26\">Special-Needs-Fund</a>, Nathan now has a new eye and loves to run and play with his friends.</p>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"Nathan - after\" title=\"Nathan - after\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIpMjAxMS8xMC8yNy8yM180OF8wMl8xNF9TTkZfYWZ0ZXIuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg0yMjV4MjU1PgY7BlQ/SNF_after.jpg\" height=\"300\" width=\"300\" /></p>',NULL,'2011-10-27 19:48:24','2011-10-27 19:55:15');
