INSERT INTO `news_items` VALUES (13,'Open House 2011','<p>We invite you to join us at Christian Aid Ministries\' twenty-sixth annual Open House on November 4 &amp; 5, 2011. CAM staff members will share firsthand reports, experiences, and slides about the work they are involved in. Get a glimpse of how your donations, prayers, and volunteer work are blessing thousands of people around the globe.</p>\r\n<h3>Location: Christian Aid Ministries warehouse, 2412 Division Highway, Ephrata, Pennsylvania</h3>\r\n<iframe marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&amp;source=s_q&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=2412+Division+Highway,+Ephrata,+Pennsylvania&amp;aq=&amp;sll=37.0625,-95.677068&amp;sspn=55.323926,135.263672&amp;vpsrc=0&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=2412+Division+Hwy,+Ephrata,+Pennsylvania+17522&amp;t=m&amp;ll=40.141615,-76.105986&amp;spn=0.019684,0.025749&amp;z=14&amp;iwloc=A&amp;output=embed\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"450\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"450\"></iframe>\r\n<small><a href=\"http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&amp;source=embed&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=2412+Division+Highway,+Ephrata,+Pennsylvania&amp;aq=&amp;sll=37.0625,-95.677068&amp;sspn=55.323926,135.263672&amp;vpsrc=0&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=2412+Division+Hwy,+Ephrata,+Pennsylvania+17522&amp;t=m&amp;ll=40.141615,-76.105986&amp;spn=0.019684,0.025749&amp;z=14&amp;iwloc=A\" style=\"color:#0000FF;text-align:left\">View Larger Map</a>\r\n</small>\r\n<h3>Area airports close to CAM</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Harrisburg	- 45 minutes from CAM</li>\r\n<li>Philadelphia	- 1 hour &amp; 15 minutes from CAM</li>\r\n<li>Baltimore	- 2 hours from CAM</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h1>Schedule of Activities</h1>\r\n<h2>Evening Slide Presentation</h2>\r\n<h3>November 4 &amp; 5 - Friday &amp; Saturday evening</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">The same slides will be shown both evenings. There should be plenty of room for everyone.</p>\r\n<h3>7:00-9:00	Slides about CAM programs</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Trail of a food parcel - Paul A. Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>A priceless hope - <em>Support-A-Widow</em> - Seth Martin, Alabama (former Liberia staff)</li>\r\n<li>Boxes of blessings - <em>Nicaragua-Adopt-A-Family</em>	- Kevin Steiner, Nicaragua</li>\r\n<li>Manna from our Heavenly Father - <em>Adopt-A-Family</em>	- Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>Help for Romania’s elderly	- Matthew Bontrager, Illinois (former Romania staff)</li>\r\n<li>“God’s eyes are on us” - Hope-for-the-Handicapped	- Seth Martin, Alabama (former Liberia staff)</li>\r\n<li>Bibles for the bush people in Liberia - <em>Bibles-for-the-World</em> - Paul Hershberger, Colorado</li>\r\n<li>Sharing Christ’s love in the land of the Bible	- Daniel Miller, Virginia (former Israel staff)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Children’s story time with Johnny Miller</h3>\r\n<ul><li>“And the Gentiles shall come to thy light . . . ” Isaiah 60:3 - <em>Jericho Road Ministries, Sponsor-A-Bible-Lesson, and Nathaniel Orphanage update</em>	Titus Miller, Romania</li>\r\n<li>Pointing America to Christ - <em>Billboard Evangelism</em>	Dwayne Stoltzfus, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>Rapid Response Teams/Disaster Response Services	- Willie Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>Tribulation, distress, persecution, and famine - <em>International Crisis Projects</em>	- David Leid, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>A dollars’ worth of health and life - <em>Gifts-That-Grow, Medicines-for-Multitudes</em>	- Kevin Steiner, Nicaragua</li>\r\n<li>Save-A-Life!	Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>Clothing blessings from afar - <em>Clothing Bundle Project</em>	- Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>Touching the lives of the fatherless - <em>Support-an-Orphan</em>	- Merle Beachy, Kenya</li>\r\n<li>Haiti-Sponsor-A-Child school program	- Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>Potential for Liberia’s farmers - <em>Seed Project</em>	- Seth Martin, Alabama (former Liberia staff)</li>\r\n<li>Working with our hands - <em>Family-Self-Support</em>	Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>Hope &amp; Opportunity - one family at a time - <em>SALT Microfinance Solutions</em>	Harold Herr, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>Value of volunteers	- Paul A. Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>Liberia, through the eyes of a child	- Elvin Stoltzfus, Liberia (not present, voice recording)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Daytime Schedule</h2>\r\n<h3>November 5 - Saturday daytime session</h3>\r\n<ul><li>7:45-9:45	Biblical Stewardship Seminar	- Paul A. Miller</li>\r\n<li>8:30-9:45	Self-guided tours of warehouse and cannery</li>\r\n<li>10:00	Singing and devotional meditation</li>\r\n<li>10:30	Manna from our Heavenly Father - <em>Adopt-A-Family</em>	- Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>10:40	Special-Needs-Fund - Seth Martin, Alabama (former Liberia staff)</li>\r\n<li>10:50	Save-A-Life!	- Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>11:05	Touching the lives of the fatherless - <em>Support-an-Orphan</em>	- Merle Beachy, Kenya</li>\r\n<li>11:20	Boxes of blessings - <em>Nicaragua-Adopt-A-Family</em>	- Kevin Steiner, Nicaragua</li>\r\n<li>11:30	Haiti-Sponsor-A-Child school program	- Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>11:40	CAM update and inform	- David Troyer, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>12:00	Lunch <em>Please bring finger foods, etc. - especially sandwiches. Thank you! Beverages will be provided. Free time to browse warehouse, displays, and book tables. Take advantage of the Open 	House special: 25% off all CAM-published books and CDs.</em>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>1:40	“And the Gentiles shall come to thy light . . . ” Isaiah 60:3 - <em>Jericho Road Ministries,        			Sponsor-A-Bible-Lesson, and Nathaniel Orphanage</em> <em>update</em>	- Titus Miller, Romania</li>\r\n<li>1:50	Hope &amp; Opportunity - one family at a time - <em>SALT Microfinance Solutions</em>	- Gary Miller, Idaho&#160;</li>\r\n<li>2:05	Rapid Response Teams/Disaster Response Services -	Paul Weaver, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>2:20	Biblical Stewardship Services	- Paul A. Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>2:25	Working with our hands - <em>Family-Self-Support</em>	- Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>2:35	Help for Romania’s elderly	- Matthew Bontrager, Illinois (former Romania staff)</li>\r\n<li>2:45	Sharing Christ’s love in the land of the Bible -	Daniel Miller, Virginia (former Israel staff)</li>\r\n<li>2:55	Pointing America to Christ - <em>Billboard Evangelism</em>	Johnny Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n</ul>','2011-10-13 16:51:00','2011-10-13 17:23:07','2011-10-19 15:37:31',NULL,NULL,'News Release','',NULL,NULL),(8,'A Ray of Hope in Their Final Years','<p>Juan and Cruz live with their crippled son Isidro in a small house beside the church where they are members. In exchange for rent, they clean the church and maintain its premises. Their only income is the $25 their children give them each month and the $10 cash they receive with their food parcel from CAM. They use the cash to buy medicines for Isidro and more food. <br />Life is difficult for elderly people in Nicaragua. Healthcare for the elderly is free, but the hospitals are unsanitary and usually do not have the proper equipment or medicines. When older people develop major health problems they often die for lack of quality treatment. These people depend on their children or extended family to survive. <br />\"Their helplessness and dependence on others are the biggest things that stand out to me,\" says Andy Yoder, CAM\'s distribution director in Nicaragua. \"Some die simply for lack of basic necessities.\"</p>\r\n<h2>Hope in Haiti</h2>\r\n<p>Madam Belia sits on the steps of her hurricane-damaged, tarp-covered house. Sunshine and strong winds have weathered the tarp. When it rains at night, she covers herself with a piece of plastic to stay dry. Nevertheless she pleasantly states, \"God is good to me. Everything in the box is so helpful. I keep you on my mind in prayer. Thank you, thank you for the food.\"</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Madam Belia is another recipient of CAM\'s <strong><a title=\"Help-for-the-Elderly\" href=\"/programs/14\">Help-for-the-Elderly (HFTE)</a> </strong>program. These older people suffer so much yet deeply appreciate the help they receive from sponsors.\r\n</p>\r\n<p><strong><a title=\"Help-for-the-Elderly\" href=\"/programs/14\">HFTE</a>\r\n</strong> recipients receive a parcel every month. Pastors from evangelical churches give us names of the poorest in their churches. CAM staff visits these families, and if they are within CAM\'s policy to receive a parcel, we add them to the program. After they are added to the list, they receive a monthly parcel until their situation improves and someone poorer needs a parcel.</p>\r\n<p>Many older people who are Christians portray a strong faith in God that He will provide for them. Many times they view the help they receive from CAM as a direct answer to their prayer for help.</p>\r\n<p>For Juan and his family, Madam Belia, and hundreds more elderly people, a monthly food parcel is a bright ray of hope in their life and more times than not, the only way they survive.</p>\r\n','2011-09-02 20:14:00','2011-09-02 20:27:40','2011-12-15 18:48:14',NULL,65,'CAM Newsletter','Madam Belia in Haiti with her treasured Help-for-the-Elderly food parcel.',14,'Help-for-the-Elderly'),(14,'On the Road  to Healing','<p>Deep potholes dot the narrow road leading to the clinic. No yellow lines run down the middle or white lines along its side, just a winding “lane” between miles of dense jungle forest. But the quality of the road is of least importance to the little girl with her foot wrapped in a dirty bandage. Or to Nyato Malu, a young man with “falling down sickness” as the Liberians call epilepsy. They are on the road that leads to a source of healing. </p>\r\n<p>Zeewhorr Community Clinic, nestled in a little town in the bush of Liberia, is a place where healing can be found. Dr. Gharweah Toe, the highest medically educated man for miles around, is a licensed physician’s assistant and the only “doctor” for hundreds of people in the area. Thanks to generous donors, Dr. Toe has fresh bandages and treatment for the little girl with the snakebite on her foot and medicine for Nyato. </p>\r\n<p>Sometimes the seizures would come on Nyato every five minutes. His mother struggled to care for her son, and her friends told her to take him to the witch doctor, but she refused. When she heard the clinic at Zeewhorr had medicine for this kind of sickness, she brought her son an hour’s walk to the clinic and is now pleased with the results. She says, “It can be fine when he on the medicines.” </p>\r\n<p>CAM supporters supply donated medicines and medical supplies to this clinic and hundreds of others throughout Liberia, Romania, El Salvador, Nicaragua, and Haiti. For most of these clinics, it’s the only way they can keep their facilities open. With God’s help and your support, people in need are on the road to healing.</p>','2011-10-27 18:57:00','2011-10-27 18:33:20','2011-12-16 17:35:16',NULL,132,'CAM Newsletter','Many people find help and healing at Zeewhorr clinic. Thanks to generous donors, Nyato, second from left, has medicine for his epilepsy.',19,'Medicines-for-Multitudes'),(9,'Light and Truth in Monrovia\'s Prison Halls','<p>Bright sunlight filters through the iron bars of the cell window, offering a false hope to the detainees inside. Cold and dark, the cell seems to snatch away any glimmer of hope and replace it with depression and stress.  Not knowing when or if they will return to civilization, the inmates have little left to live for. Unfortunately, this is life for most prisoners in Liberia.</p>\r\n<p>But some of the inmates in Monrovia, Liberia, experience something different. The cold, iron bars no longer discourage them.  Stress and depression no longer reign in the prison halls. These men have found faith in Jesus Christ, the Light and Truth of all!</p>\r\n<p>Several years ago, Light Mennonite Church in Liberia began to distribute Bible correspondence courses in prisons throughout Monrovia. These courses are published by Lamp and Light and funded by CAM\'s <strong><a title=\"News\" href=\"/programs/35\">Sponsor-A-Bible-Lesson</a>\r\n</strong> program. Inmates declare the courses to be the \"liberator of their lost souls.\" Brother Sayon, Lamp and Light office assistant, reports, \"The courses have trained up pastors, evangelists, and praying brethren within the prison . . . \"</p>\r\n<p>New believers testify the courses strengthen their faith in God. They are thankful for the knowledge they gain from their studies, and that they no longer need to be among the ignorant ones who are being destroyed (Hosea 4:6). Their daily prayer is that they will not stray from the Truth they have received.</p>\r\n<p>Thank you, supporters, for making it possible to provide Bible lessons for lost and struggling inmates in Liberia! Please pray the inmates in the dreaded prisons of Monrovia would continue walking in Truth even after they are released from prison.</p>','2011-09-02 20:39:00','2011-09-02 20:41:49','2011-12-15 18:47:58',NULL,NULL,'CAM Newsletter','',35,'Sponsor-A-Bible-Lesson'),(10,'Bibles to the Bush','<p>Liberia is a land of darkness, but many people also have a real hunger for the Word of God. This year again, God led a small team from America to bring several thousand Bibles and Christian literature to the bush parts of Liberia where some people had never owned a Bible. Pray the Gospel message will take root in these villages where spiritual darkness and superstition abound.</p>','2011-08-24 12:30:00','2011-09-06 12:33:13','2011-12-15 18:48:53',NULL,91,'CAM Newsletter','Young Liberian boy with his very own Bible',5,'Bibles-for-the-World'),(11,'My Mother Does Not Know','<p style=\"font-style: italic;\"><strong>Children\'s Corner</strong> - The true story of Rose Toe, a sponsored girl at the Peter Sayklon orphanage in Kakata, Liberia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\"My mother does not know,<br />My mother does not know,<br />My mother does not know,<br />I will let her know.\"</p>\r\n<p>I just learned this song. I learned it in February when I came to live at the Peter Sayklon orphanage in Kakata. The song means my mother does not know about Jesus. There are more verses . . . \"My father does not know, my brother does not know, my sister does not know, my people do not know.\"</p>\r\n<p>It used to be true of me. I didn\'t know about Jesus. But now I am learning about Him, and I love Him. I know He is coming again to take us home to heaven. We sing more verses to the song:&#160;</p>\r\n<p>\"Yes, I love the Lord,       <br />Yes, I love the Lord,<br />Yes, I love the Lord,<br />Down in my heart.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"He is coming again,<br />He is coming again,<br />He is coming again, <br />On judgment day.\" </p>\r\n<p>I learn many other songs at my new home. I love to sing the song, \"When We All Get to Heaven.\" After we sing this song, my orphanage mother says to us children, \"I always ask you one question, and every day I will ask you that question. You can sing so much. But are you going to sing in heaven? You sure you will be there?\"<br />We always answer, \"Yes!\" I make sure my voice is heard when I answer, \"Yes, I will be there in heaven!\"<br />Here at the orphanage, I have plenty of rice to eat and soon I will get my own notebook and pencil and go to school. My sponsor in America sends money to CAM every month and that pays for everything I need. I tell God and my sponsor, \"thank you!\"<br />I now know about Jesus. But my mother still does not know. And my people in River Gee do not know about Jesus. My orphanage mother prays with me that someday, someday soon, the people in my area will learn about Jesus. River Gee is far away, and we can\'t easily go there. But we pray someone will take them the message, and they can hear about Jesus. Just like I learned about Jesus at the orphanage.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">In southeastern Liberia, tradition has it that when a woman\'s husband dies, she is forced to marry his brother or another man within his family to carry on the family line. Sometimes the woman runs away to avoid marrying a man she does not love. After Rose\'s father died, her mother ran away so she would not be forced into marrying. Rose and her brothers Terry and David were left alone. <br />Martha Sayklon, director of the Peter Sayklon orphanage, heard of their sad story, had compassion on them, and brought them to her orphanage. Please pray for Rose and her brothers. At the orphanage, they receive love, care, and Bible teaching. Pray they will continue to feel God\'s love touch their hearts and stay safe and secure. <br />Pray also for the many people in River Gee and other parts of Africa who do not know about Jesus. Pray that someone would carry to them the message of God, His love, and His soon return.</p>','2011-08-30 13:08:00','2011-09-07 13:20:25','2011-12-15 18:48:41',NULL,69,'CAM Newsletter','Rose',1,'Sponsor-an-Orphan'),(12,'From Starving to Satisfied','<p>Baby Tee\'s face was once contorted by severe malnutrition and suffering. His mother was sick in the hospital, his father had abandoned him, and Baby Tee was left in the care of his grandmother. When his grandmother brought him to the CAM office in Liberia, our staff gave them two cans of infant formula. Two weeks later, when the staff visited them, Baby Tee was wearing an expression of utter contentment as he downed another bottle of the formula that helped save his life.</p>\r\n<p>Around the world, children suffer from neglect and undernourishment. Some make a full recovery, others do not. Thanks to God and faithful supporters, hundreds of cans of infant formula and nutritional drink mix find their way to remote corners of Liberia, Haiti, or Nicaragua where they help save other precious lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"Baby Tee, after infant formula\" title=\"Baby Tee, After Infant Formula\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIvMjAxMS8wOS8wNy8wOV81Nl8xMl80MjVfQmFieV9UZWVfQWZ0ZXIuSlBHBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg00NTB4NDUwPgY7BlQ/Baby_Tee_After.JPG\" width=\"450\" height=\"299\" /></p>','2011-08-31 13:54:00','2011-09-07 13:56:53','2011-12-15 18:48:26',NULL,72,'CAM Newsletter','Baby Tee - before infant formula',23,'Save-A-Life!'),(15,'Radiating Warmth to Hands and Hearts','<p>From the first chilly wind of October until the early weeks of May, gas and wood stoves radiate their warmth into Ukrainian homes. But buying firewood and gas quickly takes a heavy toll on the typical Ukrainian household. The average expense during one winter season is $425, a serious strain on meager incomes. A few fortunate families are able to harvest firewood on their own property. But many families, to lower heating bills, resort to heating only a portion or one room of their house. Lack of warmth is especially hard on the health of young children and the elderly and ailing.</p>\r\n<p>To help ease the hardships brought on by the long, bitter winters, CAM operates the <strong><a title=\"Warm-A-Family\" href=\"/programs/29\">Warm-A-Family</a>\r\n</strong> (WAF) program in Ukraine, Romania, and Moldova. Money to pay heating bills is distributed through pastors, who give us the names of the neediest families in their churches. In 2010, CAM was able to give funds to 778 churches, totaling 2,908 recipient families. </p>\r\n<p>One recipient of the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"Warm-A-Family\" href=\"/programs/29\">WAF</a> program in Ukraine is Vala Condrasiva. Her husband left her eighteen years ago, and she has to provide for the needs of her three children on her own. She has an income of $105 per month if she can find work cleaning houses. Vala has multiple medical problems that need attention and her oldest daughter now has cancer. Vala ignores her own medical  problems to provide for the treatment her oldest daughter needs. Her youngest daughter has an eye disease that is not curable but is stabilized with expensive treatment. </p>\r\n<p>Vala received <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"Warm-A-Family\" href=\"/programs/29\">WAF</a> funds to pay for wood to heat her small house, which used to be a barn. She says, “<strong><a title=\"/programs/30\" href=\"/programs/30\">Warm-A-Family</a>\r\n</strong> funds have made a real difference in my life; without it, it would have been very difficult to provide for my family.”</p>\r\n<p>Sister Raisa, another Ukrainian, probably echoes many other recipients’ responses: <em>“I thank you, my dear brothers and sisters in Christ, from the bottom of my heart for the help received in buying firewood for heating my house. This past winter was especially cold and hard, and my pension is small. I hardly have money for food and medicines. May the Lord reward you hundredfold!”</em>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>The <strong><a title=\"/programs/30\" href=\"/programs/30\">Warm-A-Family</a>\r\n</strong> program not only blesses needy recipients; it also rewards the distributors. Here is a word from Dean Wengerd, CAM’s Ukraine field director: “The Bible says in Proverbs 14:21, <em>Happy is the man that considers the poor.</em> It brings great joy to my heart to be involved in helping people like Vala find solutions to hard situations. I consider it a privilege to be a part of helping people who need assistance like this.”</p>','2011-10-27 18:50:00','2011-10-27 18:44:31','2011-12-15 18:47:00',NULL,133,'CAM Newsletter','Ukraine Warm-A-Family recipient Vala Condrasiva, pictured with her eldest daughter, has multiple medical problems and now her oldest daughter has cancer.',29,'Warm-A-Family'),(16,'Hope for Needy Widows','<p>“What will I make for our next meal?” “When will we eat again?” “How can I buy more charcoal so I can cook?”</p>\r\n<p>Imagine asking these questions and finding yourself in a situation with no money, no food, and almost no hope. For needy widows in Haiti, Nicaragua, Liberia, Israel, and other countries, the <strong><a title=\"/programs/28\" href=\"/programs/28\">Support-A-Widow</a>\r\n</strong> food parcels give hope to widows whose lives are clouded with poverty and uncertainty. </p>\r\n<p>Fifty-year-old Marie Denisse in Haiti has six children, but she was never married to their father. Since his death, she became a believer and decided to remain single and raise her children on her own. Their home was destroyed in the earthquake, but God has blessed them with a new home. </p>\r\n<p>She says, “The food box brings much relief to the load of caring for six children. I pray much for those who send the box. I didn’t have anything, but now God has blessed me.” </p>\r\n<p>But he saveth the poor from the hand of the mighty...so the poor hath hope.\" Job 5:15-16a</p>','2011-10-27 18:40:00','2011-10-27 18:54:45','2011-12-15 18:47:43',NULL,134,'CAM Newsletter','Marie Denisse, a widow in Haiti, is grateful for the food parcel she receives through CAM\'s Support-A-Widow program',28,'Support-A-Widow'),(17,'Spreading the Truth from North to South','<p><em>I pull my warm fur-lined coat closer as the strong wind whips around me. I, a Nenet tribal member from the Yamal Peninsula in northwest Siberia, Russia, peer off into the distance, noting the barren tundra landscape; no trees, few plants, and flat plains for many miles. As I shield my eyes from the bright sun, I notice a group of men struggling against the wind to make it to shelter. They slowly make it to our campsite, so I welcome them out of the cold and into our reindeer skin tent. Worried the weary travelers may be famished from their journey, I give them food and drink. They show their gratitude with a smile, and bring out a suitcase full of literature. They hand me</em> The Seed of Truth <em>magazine. I feel new joy and hope as I read through the magazine and discover the Gospel. </em>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>The Nenets of northwest Siberia, Russia, are not the only ones overjoyed with Christian literature. Believers in many countries are blessed and encouraged by the things they read in CAM Christian family magazines. An eleven-year old girl from Poland requested to have her own copies of <em>The Seed of Truth</em>. She says, “Such beautiful things are written for children, about birds, animals, and other interesting things. I love to read it.” In Moldova, the Vanya Muntean family, who saves the magazines to reread in the future, is deeply encouraged by the articles. On the other side of the globe, Christians’ lives in South America have been changed through <em>The Torch of Truth</em> magazines, “There are many good testimonies to tell on the enormous blessings the “Torch” has caused in so many lives, homes, and cities of our nation . . .” writes a pastor from Nicaragua.</p>\r\n<p>Through the prayers and donations of supporters like you, many lives have been changed throughout the world! Please pray for those whose lives may be touched through these magazines. </p>','2011-10-27 18:49:00','2011-10-27 19:06:28','2011-12-15 18:47:17',NULL,135,'CAM Newsletter','A group of Nenets from the Yamai Peninsula in northwestern Siberia, Russia, overjoyed with Christian literature.',3,'Christian Family Magazines'),(18,'Billboard Evangelism','<p>More than a year ago, a young Jewish girl seeking for truth, called the toll-free number on a CAM billboard and talked with one of our tele-counselors. Recently she called again and left a message, thanking him for the seed he had planted in her heart and praising God that she has received Jesus as her “Messiah” and Savior! </p>\r\n<p>CAM’s <a title=\"Billboard Evangelism\" href=\"/programs/6\"><strong>Billboard Evangelism</strong>\r\n</a> program has more than one hundred Gospel messages posted in all fifty states. You can find out more about what God is doing through these Gospel messages by reading the quarterly Billboard Evangelism newsletter. (To sign up call 330-893-4888).</p>','2011-10-27 18:48:00','2011-10-27 19:09:18','2011-12-15 18:47:32',NULL,136,'CAM Newsletter','Fargo, ND',6,''),(19,'Disaster Response Services','<p>The same way a bridge spans the gap between two mountains, volunteers through CAM’s <strong><a title=\"/programs/11\" href=\"/programs/11\">Disaster Response Services</a>\r\n\r\n</strong> span the gap between disaster and recovery for victims of a tornado, flood, hurricane, or other natural disaster.</p>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<p><img src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSImMjAxMS8xMC8yNy8yM18yN18yNF85OTdfZHJzXzEuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg0yMjV4MjU1PgY7BlQ/drs_1.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"225\" />\r\n<img style=\"width: 196px; height: 225px;\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIlMjAxMS8xMC8yNy8yM18yN18yNV84M19kcnNfMi5qcGcGOgZFVFsIOgZwOgp0aHVtYkkiDTIyNXgyNTU+BjsGVA/drs_2.jpg\" />\r\n<img style=\"width: 150px; height: 225px;\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSImMjAxMS8xMC8yNy8yM18yN18yNV8yNjhfZHJzXzMuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg0yMjV4MjU1PgY7BlQ/drs_3.jpg\" /></p>','2011-10-27 18:49:00','2011-10-27 19:31:13','2011-12-15 18:47:26',NULL,142,'CAM Newsletter','Pikeville, KY',11,''),(20,'Special-Needs-Fund','<p>Ten-year-old Nathan in Liberia was hit in the eye with a piece of rock. The eye was severely damaged and needed to be removed. His family didn’t have enough money for a prosthetic eye, but thanks to the <a title=\"/programs/26\" href=\"/programs/26\">Special-Needs-Fund</a>, Nathan now has a new eye and loves to run and play with his friends.</p>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"Nathan - after\" title=\"Nathan - after\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIpMjAxMS8xMC8yNy8yM180OF8wMl8xNF9TTkZfYWZ0ZXIuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg0yMjV4MjU1PgY7BlQ/SNF_after.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></p>','2011-10-27 19:44:00','2011-10-27 19:48:24','2011-12-15 18:46:30',NULL,144,'CAM Newsletter','Nathan - before',26,''),(21,'Free 2011 Open House CDs & cassettes','<p>The annual CAM Open House was held November 4-5, 2011. CAM staff members from our overseas locations and the United States shared firsthand reports, experiences, and slides about the work they are involved in. The talks were recorded and are available, free of charge, on CD or cassette for your information.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Saturday Sessions</h2>\r\n<h3>CD or Cassette # 1</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Devotional Meditation ~ Nolan Byler</li>\r\n<li>Adopt-A-Family ~ Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>Special-Needs-Fund ~ Seth Martin, AL (former Liberia staff member)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>CD or Cassette #2</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Save-A-Life!  ~ Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n<li>Support-an-Orphan ~ Merle Beachy, Kenya</li>\r\n<li>Nicaragua-Adopt-A-Family ~ Kevin Steiner, Nicaragua</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>CD or Cassette #3</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Haiti-Sponsor-A-Child school program ~ Steve Yoder, Haiti</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>CD or Cassette #4</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Jericho Road Ministries, Sponsor-A-Bible-Lesson, and Nathaniel Orphanage update ~ Titus Miller, Romania </li>\r\n<li>SALT Microfinance Solutions ~ Gary Miller, Idaho</li>\r\n<li>Rapid Response Teams/Disaster Response Services ~ Paul Weaver, Ohio</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>CD or Cassette #5</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Biblical Stewardship Services ~ Paul A. Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n<li>Family-Self-Support  ~ Wayne Hursh, Ukraine</li>\r\n<li>Help for Romania’s elderly ~ Matthew Bontrager, IL (former Romania staff member)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>CD or Cassette #6</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Sharing Christ’s love in the land of the Bible ~ Daniel Miller, VA (former Israel staff member)</li>\r\n<li>Billboard Evangelism  ~ Johnny Miller, Ohio</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Would you like a CD-ROM set of the evening slide presentation, complete with pictures and voice recordings?</h2>\r\n<p>To order your free copies, please...</p>\r\n<ul><li>Call us: 330-893-2428</li>\r\n<li>Email us: <a href=\"mailto:camweb@camoh.org\">camweb@camoh.org</a>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li><a title=\"/contacts/new\" href=\"/contacts/new\">Leave a comment</a>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>When ordering, please provide us with your mailing address.</p>','2011-11-14 17:47:00','2011-11-14 17:59:13','2011-12-13 20:56:46',NULL,NULL,'News Release','',NULL,NULL),(22,'A Bundle of Warmth for Needy Families','<p>In Eastern Europe, winter is just around the corner and parents are worried. What will their children wear to school if they have outgrown their only set of clothes? And how will their children walk to school without shoes or boots to protect their little feet from the cold and snow?</p>\r\n<p>Needy families in Romania usually have little or no money left to buy coats and shoes, after paying for food and utilities. Fathers have a hard time finding full-time jobs; some leave their families to earn money in other countries, but with Europe’s shaky financial situation, even those fathers do not always find work.</p>\r\n<p>To help meet these ongoing, desperate needs, CAM operates the <a title=\"/programs/9\" href=\"/programs/9\">Clothing Bundle Project</a>. Each year, supporters donate several million pounds of used, quality clothing and footwear, and thousands of warm, cozy comforters. Volunteers help sort and bale these items into bundles, and supporters’ donations help ship the bundles to needy people in Romania, Moldova, Ukraine, and other countries.</p>\r\n<p>One Romanian family said, “Ninety percent of the clothes we wear are given to us. If we wouldn’t receive the clothing bundle, we don’t know how we would be able to clothe our family. We find use for ALL the clothing in the bag.”</p>\r\n<p>Thanks to you supporters, little feet will be protected from the cold and snow this winter and parents will be able to provide the warm clothing their children need.</p>\r\n<p>“…My soul shall be joyful in my God; for he hath clothed me with the garments of salvation…” Isaiah 61:10</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"Little Romanian boys quickly dig through their clothing bundle to find clothes that will fit them and keep them warm this winter.\" title=\"Little Romanian boys quickly dig through their clothing bundle to find clothes that will fit them and keep them warm this winter.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIpMjAxMS8xMS8yOC8yMl81OF8wOV81NThfQ0JQX1JvY2EuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg0yMjV4MjU1PgY7BlQ/CBP_Roca.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"210\" /></p>','2011-11-28 20:00:00','2011-11-21 16:05:47','2012-01-06 21:12:01',NULL,152,'CAM Newsletter','“Look, the coat fits me just right!” this little girl from Ukraine seems to be saying. Her “new” coat and cap came out of a CAM clothing bundle, a gift from caring supporters in the United States.',9,'Clothing Bundle Project'),(23,'A Special Opportunity','<h2>A Special Opportunity to impact the work of the Lord with your Oil and Gas proceeds <em>(and save taxes in the process)</em>\r\n</h2>\r\n<p>The recent discovery of oil and gas reserves in shale is providing many of our friends and supporters with special opportunities and challenges to substantially impact the work of the Lord in their lifetimes. </p>\r\n<p>Energy companies are offering large mineral leases with the promise of future royalties if wells are drilled and oil and gas extracted. This windfall wealth can be a great blessing, but it also creates new personal, family, and tax issues to deal with. </p>\r\n<p>If you have been blessed with oil and gas proceeds, you may be wondering what you can do to reduce the taxes on lease and royalty income and direct more to ministry and family use. First, it is important to spend time with God the creator and owner of the minerals and this opportunity for you. The ultimate decision for how you use the proceeds lies between you the steward and God the owner to whom we will all give final account.&#160;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Some important questions to consider:</p>\r\n<ul><li>How will unexpected lease and royalty income affect our lives and our children and future generations? </li>\r\n<li>How can I reduce taxes on a large lease payment and future royalty income?</li>\r\n<li>How will future royalty values affect my estate and estate taxes?</li>\r\n<li>How should I balance providing for my loved ones and sharing this financial blessing to fund the work of the Lord?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>There are ways you can redirect your dollars, that would otherwise go toward taxes on this windfall wealth, to fund things that are important to you:</p>\r\n<ul><li>The financial needs of your local church</li>\r\n<li>Christian schooling for your children</li>\r\n<li>Church healthcare plans</li>\r\n<li>Helping the poor, orphans, and widows</li>\r\n<li>Providing Bibles to multitudes around the world who have none</li>\r\n<li>Support for missionaries who teach and preach the Gospel at home and abroad</li>\r\n<li>Establishing a charitable gift fund to distribute gifts in the future as needed</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>All of these may be accomplished through proper planning. As much as possible, it is important for you to plan in advance of signing the lease that brings this income to you.</p>\r\n<p>Christian Aid Ministries is here to help you plan to maximize benefits, avoid unnecessary taxes, and impact the work of the Lord.</p>\r\n<p>Call the CAM home office at 330-893-2428 and talk to <strong>Paul A. Miller</strong> or <strong>Eli Weaver</strong> about a free, confidential consultation to discuss managing windfall wealth from a Biblical stewardship perspective.</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"foundationred-text-bevel-web\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSI9MjAxMS8xMS8yOC8yMl8yN18zOV80NzhfZm91bmRhdGlvbnJlZF90ZXh0X2JldmVsX3dlYi5wbmcGOgZFVFsIOgZwOgp0aHVtYkkiDTIyNXgyNTU+BjsGVA/foundationred_text_bevel_web.png\" width=\"225\" height=\"135\" /></p>','2011-11-28 18:18:00','2011-11-28 19:28:35','2011-12-23 21:35:05',NULL,156,'News Release','',NULL,''),(24,'Clean Water for Kenyans','\r\n<p>Finding a good water supply is difficult for people in Kenya. Sometimes their only option is to walk several kilometers to fetch water from a muddy river or pond. Others have to stand in line for hours, waiting their turn at a public water source. </p>\r\n<p>Caren Ochieng, a sixty-six-year-old widow, lives in a small house made of dried mud walls and a tin roof, typical of houses in Kisumu, Kenya. Caren suffers from arthritis in her knees, making it difficult for her to walk far. She is grateful for the new well recently dug on her property, made possible by CAM’s <a title=\"/programs/30\" href=\"/programs/30\">Water-for-the-World</a> (WFTW) program. The well and pump are within fifty feet of her house, allowing her to fetch her daily supply of water. Others in the community also come to pump clean, fresh water for their households.</p>\r\n<p>When asked what message she would like to send to <a title=\"/programs/30\" href=\"/programs/30\">WFTW</a>\r\n sponsors, Caren stated: “I am very thankful! I pray for them and wish God’s blessing as they have shared and continue to share in this work.”</p>\r\n<p>“I will give unto him that is athirst of the fountain of the water of life freely.” Revelation 21:6b</p>','2011-11-28 19:01:00','2011-11-28 20:03:40','2011-12-23 21:36:56',NULL,158,'CAM Newsletter','Caren Ochieng with the men who helped hand-dig the well near her house',30,'Water-for-the-World'),(25,'God’s Provision in a Time of Need','<p>The children shuffle sleepily across the dirt floor to the table, ready to eat a Nicaraguan breakfast of tortillas and sour cream. Papa has already headed out to work in his corn and bean field. Mama leans over her crude kitchen counter, mixing up tortillas. Her thoughts go to the day ahead. <em>After I get the children off to school, I must finish Marcia’s laundry! I hope she can pay me this time; we need more food. Hopefully our corn will help us a little this year. </em>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Wiping her hands on her worn apron, she reaches for the flour sack, realizing it’s almost empty. Tears spring to her eyes as she pours out the last cup of flour. <em>How will we ever pay our bill at the market? They have already let us put our supplies on credit the past few weeks. I’m afraid we won’t be able to make it. </em>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Suddenly Mama’s troubled thoughts are interrupted by a cheerful “Hola!” ringing through the morning air. She follows the children as they run wide-eyed to the narrow open doorway. Her breath catches in disbelief as she sees two men carrying several boxes approach their mountain home. The food parcel! <em>Oh, thank you, Jesus, for providing for us! </em>This time her tears are of relief, thankful to God for showing His everlasting love to her poor family. </p>\r\n<p>Though the above story is imagined, poor families in the mountainous land of Nicaragua are truly overjoyed to see CAM food parcels arrive at their doorsteps. Although the parcels last only for part of a month, the recipients are grateful for the greatly needed necessities that give them a lift. Besides food and medicines, the parcels also come with Christian literature to feed spiritually hungry souls. </p>\r\n<p>Many recipients find new hope and help through <a title=\"/programs/40\" href=\"/programs/40\">Nicaragua-Adopt-A-Family</a> sponsors! Thank you for sharing your blessings. Without your sponsorships, many more Christian families in Nicaragua would continue to suffer in poverty. Please pray we can meet the needs of many more families.</p>','2011-12-06 19:31:00','2011-12-06 19:35:17','2012-01-06 21:11:52',NULL,161,'CAM Newsletter','One of the many Nicaraguan families on the receiving end of Nicaraguan-Adopt-a-Family food parcels',40,'Nicaragua-Adopt-A-Family'),(26,'Simple Gifts','<p>If you happened to stumble upon a certain small hut in Liberia, you would most likely be greeted by an elderly lady wheeling herself out onto her small porch. Mary Morris, who is seventy-six years old, lives a short distance from the CAM base in Liberia and received a wheelchair through CAM’s <a title=\"/programs/42\" href=\"/programs/42\">Hope-for-the-Handicapped</a> program. </p>\r\n<p>A year ago Mary was still healthy and active before her right leg mysteriously swelled to twice its size. Because of delayed medical attention and poor care, her legs are weak and she can no longer stand or walk. When she took her first ride in her new wheelchair, her wrinkled face lit up with delight at her new-found freedom. For handicapped people like Mary, the simple gift of a wheelchair is a special highlight in their otherwise bleak future.</p>','2011-12-06 21:31:00','2011-12-06 21:32:30','2012-01-06 21:11:41',NULL,162,'CAM Newsletter','Mary with her new wheelchair',42,'Hope for the Handicapped'),(27,'“I still remember the joy”','<p>Since the early 1980s, many thousands of food parcels have made their way across the Atlantic Ocean, sent by generous sponsors in America. God has used these parcels to answer countless prayers and help relieve the needs of struggling Christian families in Romania, Moldova, and Ukraine.</p>\r\n<p>Lidia Ulici recently wrote to tell us her joyful childhood memories of receiving food parcels during communist days in Romania. She writes: <em>Our family often speaks about the great help we received from Christian Aid Ministries during and after the harsh communist regime. I still remember the joy we felt whenever your driver showed up at our house with food, clothing, and treats for us children. I relive those emotions even as I write this letter. </em>\r\n</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">We were never allowed to open the parcels until we all got down on our knees and prayed for our sponsor and all who made the blessings possible. Often the parcels would come at the exact times we were most in need and praying for help. I appreciate so much everything you have done and continue to do for those in need.</p>\r\n<p>Although Romania joined the European Union in 2007, the economy did not improve as much as people had hoped. Incomes have stayed low, while the cost of living jumped fifty percent or more. In Eastern Europe, many groceries are twice as expensive as in the United States. For the poorest of the poor, things have improved very little, if at all.</p>\r\n<p>The <strong><a title=\"/programs/39\" href=\"/programs/39\">Adopt-A-Family</a>\r\n</strong>(AAF) food parcel program continues to minister to 3,000 needy families in Romania, Moldova, and Ukraine each month. Supporters’ donations of $69 supply 50-pound or larger parcels containing basic food and healthcare items and some Christian literature. The variety of food in the parcels is more than poor Romanian families can afford to buy; the canned meat is especially a rare treat. </p>\r\n<p>Thank you, supporters, for making a difference for Lidia Ulici and many others throughout the years. Lidia, who now lives in Canada with most of her family, hopes she can someday say a big “thank you” to the people who shared their blessings and sponsored her family through the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/39\" href=\"/programs/39\">Adopt-A-Family</a> program. She ended her letter with \"God bless you!\" </p>','2011-12-16 17:26:00','2011-12-16 17:29:11','2012-02-06 18:10:33',NULL,167,'CAM Newsletter','The Krupa children in Ukraine are thankful for the yummy food their mother makes using items from the food parcel. Their father has a part-time construction job, but this income is insufficient for the needs of the family.',39,'Adopt-A-Family'),(28,'Blind but not begging','<p>Life is hard for many people in Ghana, Africa. For Sylvester Amman, it became even more difficult in 2004 when he lost his eyesight in an accident. But, in spite of his blindness, Sylvester was determined to find a way to provide for his family. He tried many things and finally took training to learn to make soap.</p>\r\n<p>Although Sylvester had learned a trade, he had no money to purchase the needed equipment for soap making. In November 2010, Sylvester first heard about CAM’s <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/22\" href=\"/programs/22\">SALT Microfinance Solutions</a> program. Sylvester, along with others in his village, applied for a small loan and then waited patiently.</p>\r\n<p>In April 2011, Sylvester heard that a church in the United States had given money to fund an entire loan family (accountability group of loan recipients from the same community), and his group had been chosen as recipients. Sylvester was thrilled!</p>\r\n<p>Today Sylvester makes five hundred bars of soap every week and is overjoyed to finally support himself and his family. He said with a big grin, “I don’t have to be a beggar just because I’m blind. I love the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/22\" href=\"/programs/22\">SALT Microfinance</a> program and am so glad God allowed me to be part of it. I pray God will bless and cause you to prosper so more can be given to this program to bless many others.”</p>\r\n<p>In addition to a loan, and maybe even more important, Sylvester and his fellow loan recipients receive ongoing spiritual teaching and business training. As contributions are received for the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/22\" href=\"/programs/22\">SALT Microfinance</a>program, we look forward to helping many more families support themselves.</p>','2011-12-16 17:20:00','2011-12-16 17:32:35','2012-02-06 18:10:45',NULL,168,'CAM Newsletter','Blind Ghana loan recipient Sylvester making soap.',22,'SALT Microfinance Solutions'),(29,'Save-A-Life!','<p><img rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"SAL_before(1)\" title=\"SAL_before(1)\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbBlsHOgZmSSItMjAxMS8xMi8xOS8yMl81N18zOF85N19TQUxfYmVmb3JlXzFfLmpwZwY6BkVU/SAL_before_1_.jpg\" height=\"204\" width=\"613\" /></p>\r\n<p>Rosecarline came to the CAM clinic in La Source, Haiti, in August 2010. She was extremely dehydrated and malnourished and suffered from a cleft lip and palate.</p>\r\n<p><img rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"SAL_after(1)\" title=\"SAL_after(1)\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbBlsHOgZmSSItMjAxMS8xMi8xOS8yMl81N18zN185NTJfU0FMX2FmdGVyXzFfLmpwZwY6BkVU/SAL_after_1_.jpg\" height=\"204\" width=\"613\" /></p>\r\n<p>Today Rosecarline has a beautiful smile and, as a result of receiving nutrition through CAM’s <strong><a title=\"/programs/23\" href=\"/programs/23\">Save-A-Life!</a>\r\n</strong> program, she no longer suffers from malnutrition. </p>','2011-12-19 19:56:00','2011-12-19 19:59:05','2012-01-13 17:08:21',NULL,NULL,'CAM Newsletter','',23,''),(30,'Bright smiles & new wheelchairs','<p>Maria Luz in Rama, Nicaragua, has polio, a disease that confines her to a wheelchair. But Maria doesn’t allow her handicap to give her a bleak outlook on life. Rather than focus on her disability, she turns her mind to her studies.</p>\r\n<p>“This girl is very inspiring,” says CAM staff member Kevin Steiner. “She makes drawings of Nicaragua’s national bird and sells them for a dollar each to help pay her university costs.” Maria lives with her mother whose husband abandoned them. The only other income the two have is from the homemade tortillas her mother sells. As Maria shades the green throat of Nicaragua’s national bird, the smile on her face reflects the gratitude in her heart for those who provided her wheelchair through CAM’s <a title=\"/programs/13\" href=\"/programs/13\">Gifts-That-Grow</a> (GTG) program.</p>\r\n<p>On the outskirts of another Nicaraguan town lives Eduardo, an eight-year-old boy who suffers from paralysis. His father earns a meager wage as a rickshaw (taxi) driver in town. Since this is the family’s only income, they find it difficult to get proper care for Eduardo. Through God’s provision, and support of CAM donors, Eduardo now has a bright smile on his face and a wheelchair to help him get around. </p>\r\n<p>Each year, CAM has the opportunity to receive millions of dollars’ worth of free medicines, wheelchairs, soap, footwear, liquid nutrition, and many other valuable items. Corporations and organizations offer these products for humanitarian reasons or when items are overstocked, discontinued, or nearing expiration. Though the products are donated, CAM has procurement fees and trucking costs to bring them to our Pennsylvania warehouse. Every $1 donated to the <a title=\"/programs/13\" href=\"/programs/13\">Gifts-That-Grow</a> program helps procure $200 worth of free products and ship them to needy families and individuals.</p>\r\n<p>On behalf of Maria, Eduardo, and many others around the world, we say \'thank you\' for your continued support of the <a title=\"/programs/13\" href=\"/programs/13\">Gifts-That-Grow</a> program. For recipients, this program is a blessing and often an answer to prayer. By the grace of God and supporters’ help, many poor, sick, and handicapped children and adults have new hope!</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"Eduardo smiles brightly from his new wheelchair.\" title=\"Eduardo smiles brightly from his new wheelchair.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIqMjAxMi8wMS8wNi8yM181NF81MV85X0dUR19lZHVhcmRvLmpwZwY6BkVUWwg6BnA6CnRodW1iSSINMjI1eDI1NT4GOwZU/23_54_51_9_GTG_eduardo.jpg\" height=\"225\" width=\"225\" /></p>','2012-01-06 20:51:00','2012-01-06 20:55:52','2012-02-06 18:10:11',NULL,181,'CAM Newsletter','Wheelchair recipient, Maria Luz, sells drawings of Nicaragua’s national bird to help pay for her school costs.',13,'Gifts-That-Grow'),(31,'Does Jesus care?','<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">This story is based on a true account, written from the imagined perspective of a homeowner. The setting is Hackleburg, Alabama, where F-4 and F-5 tornados left destruction and despair in their wake.</p>\r\n<p>Our world has crashed around us. The unsightly debris scattered all over our twenty-one acres and beyond represents the once comfortable and happy life of the past forty years with my wife. The beautiful trees surrounding our home are a huge, twisted, ugly mass of destruction. The rolling land, usually so beautiful in spring, now looks naked and bare. Our house is scattered to the four winds. Only a few walls remain where my wife and I and our six-week-old grandson huddled in fear during the terrible storm. Our great grandson now has no mother; she was killed in her house a quarter mile away.</p>\r\n<p>I stand in the midst of this destruction. My heart is bleeding. The losses and dramatic changes in my life seem more than I can bear. I believe in you, God, but I need some reassurance that you care and know about my plight. Does Jesus care when my sad heart aches till it nearly breaks? Does He know the hurt and pain I feel? Does Jesus care about me now? Right now I’m not sure.</p>\r\n<p>My thoughts are interrupted by a touch on my shoulder. I look up to see a man beside me who says he is here to help. He has tears in his eyes and a catch in his voice. His hand on my shoulder feels like healing salve on an open wound. No, the pain doesn’t go away, but here is someone who really cares—I can feel it.</p>\r\n<p>Trucks and equipment start coming in my driveway. The leader of the group asks, “What do you want done?” I’m overwhelmed. They have chain saws, loaders for brush and debris removal, a trailer full of equipment, and, best of all, they have manpower! </p>\r\n<p>Does Jesus care when the burdens press and the cares distress? I’m beginning to think He does.</p>\r\n<p>A father and son start sawing away branches. Several teenage boys full of youthful energy enthusiastically join in. These people left their jobs and families for a week and voluntarily traveled many miles to help us in our dilemma. Why did they do it? I realize it must be the love of God at work in their lives that motivated them and brought them here. I believe God answered my big question—does Jesus really care? Here is living proof—Jesus knows all about us and He does care!</p>\r\n<p>Oh yes, He cares, I know He cares. His heart is touched with my grief! I don’t know why God allowed this storm to happen. But in the midst of it all, I’ve been shown He cares. Yes, the future still looks dark and uncertain. But thank you, God, for bringing a glimmer of hope through the loving labors of your faithful servants.</p>\r\n<p>—By Phil Schrock, Rapid Response Team coordinator</p>\r\n','2012-01-06 21:00:00','2012-01-06 21:02:44','2012-03-23 19:21:29',NULL,180,'CAM Newsletter','Hackleburg, AL',11,'Disaster Response Services'),(32,'Help-for-the-Elderly','<p>Florica in southern Romania ekes out a living from her garden. With no other income, she depends largely on her monthly food parcel from CAM to survive. Thanks to her sponsor, she has basic food and healthcare items to help her get through each month. She also finds encouragement for her soul through the Christian literature that comes with the parcels.</p>\r\n<p>Thousands of elderly people in Romania, Moldova, Ukraine, Haiti, Nicaragua, and Liberia live in very poor conditions and struggle to survive. <a title=\"/programs/14\" href=\"/programs/14\">Help-for-the-Elderly</a> parcels bring hope and help to at least some of these struggling, vulnerable people in their sunset years. Knowing that somewhere, someone cares about them encourages their hearts; often the parcels are an answer to their prayers.</p>\r\n<p>If you would like to bless needy elderly people, please use the <strong>“Donate Now”</strong> button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>','2012-01-11 20:06:00','2012-01-11 20:08:26','2012-01-11 20:08:26',NULL,184,'CAM Newsletter','Florica',14,'Help-for-the-Elderly'),(33,'Biblical Stewardship Services','<h2>Charitable Gift Annuities</h2>\r\n<p>This is a way for older supporters to generate income for the rest of their lives while making a charitable gift to Christian Aid Ministries. A Charitable Gift Annuity is an agreement between you and Christian Aid Ministries Foundation. In exchange for your non-refundable gift of cash or other property, CAMF will pay you a specified annuity for the rest of your life. The annual amount is fixed at the time you make the gift, and does not fluctuate with the economy, so you know how much income you will receive every year. The rate is determined by your age, as established by the American Council on Gift Annuities. You will receive an income tax charitable deduction for a portion of your gift in the year it was given.</p>\r\n<p>Each year you will also receive a tax statement from CAMF indicating the breakdown of your taxable and tax exempt annuity income for the previous year. Regular annuity payments will continue until your death, when the remaining balance of your original gift will be used in Christian Aid Ministries’ programs.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Seminars:</strong> Interested in hosting a Biblical Stewardship Seminar in your area? Please call Paul A. Miller at 330.893.2428 to schedule.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>Free literature:\r\n</strong> </h3>\r\n<ul><li>Send me FREE, quarterly Biblical Stewardship and Estate Planner</li>\r\n<li>Send me FREE Will and Estate Planning Guide.</li>\r\n<li>Send me free Biblical Stewardship Seminar CD: _______(amount)&#160;</li>\r\n<li>Send me information about Donor Advised Funds&#160;</li>\r\n<li>Send me information about Charitable Trusts&#160;</li>\r\n<li>Send me information about Charitable Bequests</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Charitable gift annuities:</strong> </h3>\r\n<ul><li>Send me information about a gift annuity, based on the following:</li>\r\n<li>Annuity amount ____________________________</li>\r\n<li>Date of birth _______________ Spouse’s date of birth _______________</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>We will prepare a personal proposal to show you:</h3>\r\n<ul><li>How much annual income you will receive for the rest of your life</li>\r\n<li>How much of your annual income will be tax-free</li>\r\n<li>How much your income tax charitable deduction will be</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">You are under no obligation to proceed with a gift.</p>\r\n<h3>To order:</h3>\r\n<ul><li>Call us: 330-893-2428</li>\r\n<li>Email us: <a title=\"camweb@camoh.org\" href=\"mailto:camweb@camoh.org\"></a>\r\n<a title=\"camweb@camoh.org\" href=\"mailto:camweb@camoh.org\">camweb@camoh.org</a>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><a title=\"/contacts/new\" href=\"/contacts/new\">Leave a comment</a>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>When ordering, please provide us with the following information:</h3>\r\n<ul><li>NAME</li>\r\n<li>Spouse Name</li>\r\n<li>Mailing Address</li>\r\n<li>Phone</li>\r\n<li>Email <em>(optional)</em>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Find out more about <a title=\"/about-cam/biblical-stewardship-services\" href=\"/about-cam/biblical-stewardship-services\">Biblical Stewardship Services</a>.<a title=\"/about-cam/biblical-stewardship-services\" href=\"/about-cam/biblical-stewardship-services\"></a>\r\n</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSI9MjAxMS8xMS8yOC8yMl8yN18zOV80NzhfZm91bmRhdGlvbnJlZF90ZXh0X2JldmVsX3dlYi5wbmcGOgZFVFsIOgZwOgp0aHVtYkkiDTIyNXgyNTU+BjsGVA/foundationred_text_bevel_web.png\" height=\"135\" width=\"225\" /></p>','2012-01-05 17:08:00','2012-01-13 17:15:53','2012-01-13 17:23:09',NULL,NULL,'News Release','',NULL,'To educate, motivate, and assist our supporters in Biblical Stewardship Planning'),(34,'Middle East Ministries','<p>CAM’s goal for ministering in Israel is to share the love of Jesus with people who inhabit the land of the Bible. Although Jesus is the area’s most famous resident, very few of His followers can be found in this part of the world. Through <strong><a title=\"/programs/36\" href=\"/programs/36\">Middle East Ministries</a>\r\n</strong> (MEM), CAM supporters provide food parcels, self-help resources, wheelchairs, and other aid to needy people in Israel, Gaza, and West Bank.</p>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<p>If you would like to help minister to the many varied needs in the Middle East, please use the <strong>“Donate Now”</strong> button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>','2012-01-17 07:55:00','2012-01-17 08:01:36','2012-03-23 19:21:12',NULL,196,'CAM Newsletter','',36,''),(35,'The terror we went through','<p>by Gloria Miller, CAM secretary in Liberia</p>\r\n<p>Hannah, Joshua, and Ebenezer Gbatahlee sat in front of us in a little schoolroom, while their uncle John told us their story and how they came to be eligible for the CAM orphan program.</p>\r\n<p>Uncle John said, “When the war really intensified, I was hiding in the bush, but my brother, he was in the village when the Mandingos came. Since he was a young man, right away they just thought he was a Charles Taylor man. So they wanted to kill him.</p>\r\n<p>“The people begged for him, but to no avail. The soldiers, they just butchered him, they cut him into pieces. This man that they killed, he was my brother. And he was Hannah, Joshua, and Ebenezer’s father.</p>\r\n<p>“As for me, I was hiding in the bush when this happened. Otherwise, the Mandingos would have killed me too. They killed six in my family.</p>\r\n<p>“But this is the children’s story. Their ma, it is unknown where she is now.  Hannah didn’t even know the story until the other day, and I had to tell her ‘Na Mind’ because she started crying.</p>\r\n<p>“And that is the terror we went through.”</p>\r\n<p><img rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"sao\" title=\"sao\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbBlsHOgZmSSIkMjAxMi8wMS8yNC8xNl8zNF80N184MjZfc2FvLmpwZwY6BkVU/sao.jpg\" height=\"188\" width=\"614\" /></p>\r\n<p>Uncle John said it with a sense of finality, like now it’s time to move on to the next subject, like it’s time to go for lunch or something trivial like that.</p>\r\n<p>And those three children, sitting across from me on the bench in that little classroom, you can’t tell me it didn’t affect them. </p>\r\n<p>Many of the orphans in Liberia don’t know their whole story. Or the true story. The adults in their lives hide it from them. But not talking about it doesn’t take it away. </p>\r\n<p>I just hope, I really hope, that when the orphans find out their true story someone will be there to tell them it’s alright to cry. Someone will be there to care for them. Someone will be there to tell them ‘Na Mind.’ That it is ok now. And they are loved and safe from the terror they went through.</p>\r\n<h3>CAM-sponsored orphanages</h3>\r\n<p>Due to years of civil war, disease, and broken homes, many children in Liberia find themselves alone. CAM sponsors provide 1,700 children at 43 orphanages with food, soap, vitamins, and The Seed of Truth magazine each month. Other items are given as available—mattresses for the dorms, fabric to sew clothes, desks and chairs for the orphanage schools—things generous donors send from the states and things NEEDED at the orphanages.</p>\r\n<p>One major event in the orphan program is the youth retreat CAM holds every January. All sponsored youth ages sixteen and up attend the two-day retreat. Liberian and American speakers teach on subjects such as witchcraft, finding purpose in life, and moral purity.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"These girls just received their monthly food box from their sponsors.\" title=\"These girls just received their monthly food box from their sponsors.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSItMjAxMi8wMS8yNC8xNl8zN18yM18zMDRfc2FvX2NoaWxkcmVuLmpwZwY6BkVUWwg6BnA6CnRodW1iSSINNDUweDQ1MD4GOwZU/sao_children.jpg\" height=\"323\" width=\"364\" /></p>\r\n<h3>Church orphan program  </h3>\r\n<p>CAM also sponsors approximately 750 children who live with guardians rather than in orphanages. Many of the children are not able to go to school until after they are on CAM’s orphan sponsorship program. We work alongside churches and contact pastors to ensure the children are getting the care and food they need.</p>\r\n<p>To help sponsor an orphan in Liberia, Kenya, and India, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>','2012-01-24 13:32:00','2012-01-24 13:39:12','2012-03-23 19:21:03',NULL,222,'CAM Newsletter','',1,'Sponsor-an–Orphan'),(36,'Schedule of Events - Feb & March','<h2>Florida presentations</h2>\r\n<h3>CAM Update</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">Slides and up-to-date reports about CAM programs, by staff member Jon Stoltzfus.</p>\r\n<p><strong>February 26, 2012 - 6:00 p.m.</strong> <br />Palm Grove Mennonite - Sarasota, FL <br />Contact: Jr. Weaver - 941-356-9048</p>\r\n<h3>CAM Open House slides</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">See and hear the slide presentation shared by our field staff at the 2011 CAM Open House.</p>\r\n<p><strong>February 28, 2012 - 7:00 p.m.</strong> <br />Pleasant View Mennonite - Zephyrhills, FL <br />Contact: Marvin Yoder - 352-523-1692 <br /></p>\r\n<p><strong>February 29, 2012 - 7:00 p.m.</strong> <br />Tourist Mennonite - Sarasota, FL <br />Contact: David Graber - 941-371-8991</p>\r\n<p><strong>March 4, 2012 - 7:00 p.m.</strong>\r\n<br />Sunnyside Mennonite - Sarasota, FL<br />Contact: Bill Yoder - 941-650-1350</p>\r\n<h3>Biblical Stewardship Seminar</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">This seminar is helpful if you need to make or update your will, want to design or review your estate plan to minimize or avoid estate and capital gains taxes and maximize charitable giving, and other stewardship issues.</p>\r\n<p><strong>March 2, 2012 - 9:00 a.m. and 6:00 p.m.</strong>\r\n<br />Tourist Mennonite - Sarasota, FL <br />Contact: David Graber - 941-371-8991</p>\r\n<h2>Pennsylvania presentations</h2>\r\n<h3>CAM Update</h3>\r\n<p><strong>March 16, 2012 - 7:00 p.m.</strong> <br />Zimmerman’s Harness Shop - Millmont, PA<br />Contact: Elvin Zimmerman - 570-966-4583</p>\r\n<h2>Maryland presentations</h2>\r\n<h3>CAM Open House slides</h3>\r\n<p><strong>March 20, 2012 - 7:00 p.m.</strong> <br />Pleasant Valley Community Center - Oakland, MD <br />Contact: Dan Yoder - 301-501-2483</p>\r\n<h2>Missouri presentations</h2>\r\n<h3>CAM Open House slides</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Thursday, March 8, 2012 - 7:00 p.m.</strong>\r\n<br />Olive Hill AM School <br />29820 Olive Branch Rd.<br />Sedalia, MO 65301<br />Contact: Roger Kropf— 660-287-2008</p>\r\n<h2>Iowa presentations</h2>\r\n<h3>CAM Open House slides</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Friday, March 9, 2012 - 7:00 p.m.</strong>\r\n<br />Pathway Christian School<br />5764 Highway 1 SW<br />Kalona, IA 52247<br />Contact: David Lee Miller - 319-656-2977</p>','2012-02-06 16:30:00','2012-02-06 16:39:24','2012-02-06 16:39:24',NULL,262,'CAM Newsletter','',NULL,''),(37,'God still cares','<p>Every month, more than a thousand families in Haiti and Liberia receive help through CAM’s <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/2\" href=\"/programs/2\">International-Feed-A-Family</a> (IFAF) program. The <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/2\" href=\"/programs/2\">IFAF</a> food parcels, provided by sponsors, go to families not able to provide for themselves. The parcels contain basic foods, healthcare items, and some Christian literature.</p>\r\n<p>Sainase Nelson, a widow from Fond Parisien, Haiti, had a stroke a number of years ago and cannot support herself. Her young grandson David lives with her. She says, “If I would not get this food box, I don’t know what I would do. My daughters have to support themselves, because I cannot help them, and they do not have a dad. I’m thankful for the people who make this possible for us.” Sainase prays God’s blessing on you supporters for your willingness to help them.</p>\r\n<p>Blind Thamas Stelus, who lives in a small house in Haiti with his extended family, says, “The box helps me and my family a lot. Thank you so very much, and may God bless you as you have blessed me.”</p>\r\n<p>The list of testimonies could go on and on. <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/2\" href=\"/programs/2\">IFAF</a> parcels are more than just food items packaged in a box for people to eat. They bring hope to those who have no hope, life to those who struggle for life, and most importantly, they convey the message that God still cares for those in need.</p>\r\n<p>To help ease poverty and suffering for hungry families in Haiti and Liberia, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>\r\n<h3>A $39 donation provides a 35-pound or larger parcel.</h3>','2012-02-06 17:57:00','2012-02-06 18:00:00','2012-03-23 19:20:46',NULL,264,'CAM Newsletter','For Charite Louis in Haiti, a monthly food parcel helps ensure her grandchildren will not go to school hungry.',2,'International-Feed-A-Family'),(38,'Gospel billboards draw souls to repentance','<p>“I appreciate seeing a billboard like this,” said Richard after driving past a CAM billboard near Edgewood, New Mexico. “So many other billboards are destructive and ruining to the mind and heart, but this one is right to the point.”</p>\r\n<p>The message Richard saw, <em>Where are you going? Heaven or Hell</em>, is one of nine Gospel messages sponsors post on highway billboards across America. With approximately 100 messages in all fifty states, the potential audience is an estimated 3.4 million people each day.</p>\r\n<p>Our tele-counselors are a very vital part of the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/6\" href=\"/programs/6\">Billboard Evangelism</a> program. They try to be available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week to answer the thousands of calls that come through the toll-free number posted on the billboards. Often their “soft answers turn away wrath.” After a conversation with a tele-counselor concerning our billboard in Las Vegas, Nevada, one caller, Mark, told us he was prepared for conflict and thought he was going to get a brick wall when he called. “But to my surprise,” he said, “I got a listener! That helps me believe in well-meaning Christians more.”</p>\r\n<p>The Gospel messages are touching many people, and the Holy Spirit is drawing souls to repentance. Phil saw a CAM billboard in Westminster, Maryland, and called in, saying, “For some time now, I have felt restless and unfulfilled. I was on drugs and my life was empty. I said, ‘God, please help me!’ Then on my way home from work, I saw the sign with a number to call for help, so I decided to call. Now here I am. God must have heard my heart cry. I really do want to get back; I just don’t know how to do it. I need help!” Our tele-counselor had the wonderful opportunity of leading this soul back to God. </p>\r\n<p>We offer Christian literature packets to seeking callers; the packets include a Bible, various booklets, tracts, and CDs that pertain to their specific need. Thousands of pieces of literature are being sent to homes all across America. Veronica was one recipient. During her initial call after seeing our billboard near Kansas City, Missouri, she shared her desire for deliverance from sin. Two months after we sent her the packet of literature, she called again to tell us that she has repented of her sinful practices and committed her life to the Lord!</p>\r\n<p>We are in a spiritual battle—the enemy is active and we need your prayers! God is working through the billboard messages, and we continue to add needy souls to our prayer list. </p>\r\n<p>In the urgent effort to help point America to Christ, it is the goal of the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/6\" href=\"/programs/6\">Billboard Evangelism</a> program to install many more Gospel messages throughout this large and spiritually needy country. We are currently reaching <em>only one percent of the U.S. population</em>. As we monitor the billboard calls per location, we see the most calls come from un-churched areas. We would like to install Gospel billboards in more of these areas as we have funds.</p>\r\n<p>To help post Gospel messages across the United States and help point people to Christ, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>\r\n<p>“There is joy in the presence of the angels of God over one sinner that repents” (Luke 15:10).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Each $1 you donate gives 1,600 people the opportunity to see a Gospel message every day.</strong>\r\n</p>','2012-02-06 18:04:00','2012-02-06 18:08:42','2012-03-23 19:20:36',NULL,263,'CAM Newsletter','A CAM billboard in Charleston, WV, points travelers to the Creator',6,'Billboard Evangelism'),(39,'Winter emergency in Romania','<p>Record snowfall and extreme temperatures in Romania have caused the deaths of more than eighty-five people. Hundreds of houses are buried in snow and numerous villages isolated by deep drifting. Some people are digging tunnels from their houses to get to their animals. Many roads are closed and over three hundred train routes cancelled.</p>\r\n<p>Since the massive snowstorm hit an area of Romania that usually sees little snow, many poor people were caught unprepared and without reserves of food or firewood. Now many are unable to get out to buy food. Some have cut down their garden trees for firewood. Relief efforts are being made by the government to reach isolated areas by helicopter and army vehicles. But believers in these villages are not looked on favorably and are treated unfairly when aid is distributed.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"A man standing where there used to be a road.\" title=\"A man standing where there used to be a road.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbBlsHOgZmSSIjMjAxMi8wMy8wMi8yMV8wN18zM185OV93ZXIuanBnBjoGRVQ/wer.jpg\" height=\"354\" width=\"450\" /></p>\r\n<p>CAM is responding to this emergency by providing food and funds for heating and other needs. After the enormous amount of snow melts, there will probably be more needs caused by flooding.</p>\r\n<p>Please pray for the suffering people in Romania and for those trying to be a help and channel of blessing.</p>\r\n<p>If you would like to help, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to make a one-time donation using your credit card or bank account. </p>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">Should more funds come in than are needed for this purpose, the balance will be used in other <a title=\"/programs/15\" href=\"/programs/15\">International Crisis</a> projects. </p>','2012-02-16 18:27:00','2012-02-16 18:28:25','2012-03-29 16:34:46',NULL,285,'News Release','A house in Romania buried in snow.',NULL,'International Crisis Project '),(40,'Conflict in Syria','<p>More than five thousand people have died as the country of Syria stands on the brink of a major civil war. As is usually the case during fighting and unrest, the common people, especially the elderly and the children, suffer along with the rest of the population. </p>\r\n<p>Thousands of Syrian refugees are streaming into Jordan, Lebanon, and Turkey despite freezing rains and military opposition. As the fighting worsens, Syria’s neighbors are bracing for a refugee crisis of epic proportions. </p>\r\n<p>CAM has already provided food and other aid for needy families in Syria and refugees in neighboring countries, and is researching the possibility of providing additional assistance. </p>\r\n<p>If you would like to help meet the needs of people suffering from Syria’s conflict, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to make a one-time donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>','2012-02-16 18:30:00','2012-02-16 18:31:19','2012-02-16 18:31:19',NULL,267,'News Release','This boy, along with his parents and ten siblings, fled to neighboring Jordan after protests started in Syria last year. Since then, they have been living in this tent. ',43,''),(41,'Become a monthly sponsor—make a difference','<p>Your monthly gifts can make a big difference for an orphan child, a needy family, or a sick person in Romania, Moldova, Ukraine, Nicaragua, Haiti, Liberia, Israel, or other countries. Often just the thought that a sponsor cares gives hope to these needy people. If you would like to be the “hands and feet of Jesus” by becoming a monthly sponsor, please go to the <a title=\"/programs\" href=\"/programs\">program of your choice</a> and select Monthly Donation. You will be able to pay your sponsorship with your bank account or credit card. </p>','2012-02-10 17:26:00','2012-02-21 17:29:13','2012-03-02 18:00:38',NULL,272,'CAM Newsletter','Adopt-A-Family food parcel recipients',NULL,''),(42,'Helping families in emergency situations','<p>An unexpected medical expense or unforeseen disaster can quickly spiral a family’s financial situation out of control. In Romania and Ukraine, an average family usually has just enough income to buy the everyday necessities, and when a surprising misfortune erupts, they feel trapped by this new liability and must now fight their way out of the debt. The weight can seem impossible to overcome.</p>\r\n<p>Maria Tiron, a mother of nine in Romanesti, Romania, was experiencing dizziness, numbness, and liver problems. She finally decided to go for medical tests but had only four dollars. She gave two dollars toward the family’s debt at the local grocery store and the other two she spent for a ride to the CAM office to ask for help. Thanks to funds from donors, CAM was able to give Maria $69 USD from the <strong><a title=\"/programs/26\" href=\"/programs/26\">Special-Needs-Fund</a> </strong>to help pay for her medical tests. She was very grateful, since she had nowhere else to turn. Her husband has back problems and cannot work, and the family lives off the children’s state allocation, which is only $110 per month.</p>\r\n<p>Irimia, a father of seven in Salcea, Romania, suffers from colon cancer and has no job. The family depends on the children’s state allocation for their monthly income. Can you imagine how a father must feel using money that would normally be used to feed his family for medication to preserve his own health? The $86 USD Irimia received from the <strong><a title=\"/programs/26\" href=\"/programs/26\">Special-Needs-Fund</a>\r\n</strong> will provide the medication he needs for at least a little while.</p>\r\n<p>“The <strong><a title=\"/programs/26\" href=\"/programs/26\">Special-Needs-Fund</a> </strong>is a very important program,” says Dean Wengerd, our field director in Ukraine. “It helps families out of emergency situations.”  One-year-old Dasha, daughter of Andrei and Lyuda Gerasimenko in Ukraine, was diagnosed with a nephroblastoma of the left kidney. For treatment, she needs chemotherapy and surgery to remove the cancerous tumor and the kidney. This treatment costs more than 20 thousand hryvnas ($2,500 USD)—a discouraging amount for a family struggling in poverty. CAM gave the family $900 USD to help cover some of the cost. They say, “We thank you wholeheartedly for your help! May the Lord richly bless you!”</p>\r\n<h3>A smile of hope</h3>\r\n<p>This little Mayangna Indian girl was born with a cleft palate and needed an operation. But in her remote village in the mountains of Nicaragua, there was little hope for medical assistance. </p>\r\n<p><img alt=\"SN\" title=\"SN\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbBlsHOgZmSSIjMjAxMi8wMi8yMS8yMF8zMV80M18xODFfU04ucG5nBjoGRVQ/SN.png\" height=\"214\" width=\"421\" /></p>\r\n<p>Through the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/26\" href=\"/programs/26\">Special-Needs-Fund</a>, CAM paid the lodging, food, and bus fare for her and her mother to travel sixteen hours to Chinandega where she received an operation through Operation Smile.</p>\r\n<p>This little one will eventually need to go back for follow-up surgery, but thanks to supporters of the Special-Needs-Fund, she has a bright smile and hope and health in her future.</p>\r\n<p>The <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/26\" href=\"/programs/26\">Special-Needs-Fund</a> is used for difficult situations often related to medical cases, house fires, funeral expenses, and other emergency cases. If you would like to help make the load lighter for people in need, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.  </p>','2012-02-10 17:29:00','2012-02-21 17:37:33','2012-03-23 19:20:20',NULL,274,'CAM Newsletter','At the CAM office in Patrauti, Romania, Maria Tiron receives a gift from the Special-Needs-Fund to cover her medical expenses.',26,'Special-Needs-Fund'),(43,'An answered prayer','<p>Lena Opanasuk in Ukraine lives on a mere $140 USD a month, while struggling to pay a $4,300 USD debt. Her husband left her four years ago, leaving her to raise their two children alone. One evening, overwhelmed, Lena pled with God to provide for their needs.</p>\r\n<p>A few days later, Lena received money through CAM’s <a title=\"/programs/29\" href=\"/programs/29\">Warm-A-Family</a> program to help pay her heating bills. Since heating costs are high in Ukraine, this took a tremendous weight off her financial problems. Overjoyed, Lena tearfully praised God for this amazing answer to prayer.</p>\r\n<p>If you want to help families in Ukraine, Romania, or Moldova through the harsh winter months, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to make a one-time donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>','2012-02-10 18:01:00','2012-03-02 18:02:52','2012-03-23 19:20:07',NULL,282,'CAM Newsletter','Lena and her children were blessed with funds from the Warm-A-Family program.',29,'Warm-a-Family'),(44,'Destructive tornadoes strike USA','<p>On March 1-2 a chain of tornadoes cut a 1,000-mile swath of destruction from the Midwest to the Gulf of Mexico. The tornadoes pummeled Indiana and Kentucky, with Alabama, Georgia, Ohio and Tennessee overrun as well. Friday\'s storms came on top of severe weather earlier in the week in the Midwest and brought the overall death toll from the unseasonably early storms to at least 50 people. These storms came less than a year after a series of tornadoes caused some of the worst insured losses in U.S. history. (Reuters)</p>\r\n<p>The Indiana towns of Marysville and Henryville were hit especially hard. “Marysville is completely gone” a witness said after surveying the damage. The scene around town is solemn and still as residents pick through what’s left of their belongings. (Time)</p>\r\n<p>CAM <a title=\"/programs/41\" href=\"/programs/41\">Rapid Response</a> units are currently on the ground helping to cleanup in <strong>Marysville, IN</strong>; <strong>Henryville, IN</strong>; and in <strong>West Liberty, KY</strong>, and they plan to help in <strong>Athens, AL</strong> as well. Last week Rapid Response units worked in <strong>Harrisburg, IL</strong>;<strong> Monterery, TN</strong>; and in <strong>Branson, MO</strong>.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"Rapid Response volunteers are clearing away the brush piles from a farmer’s place in Marysville, IN that got hit very hard by tornadoes.\" title=\"Rapid Response volunteers are clearing away the brush piles from a farmer’s place in Marysville, IN that got hit very hard by tornadoes.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSImMjAxMi8wMy8wNy8yMl81Ml81Ml8yNDJfY2hhb3MuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg00NTB4NDUwPgY7BlQ/chaos.jpg\" height=\"300\" width=\"450\" /><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"Rapid Response team members working to clear away the brush piles with loaders\" title=\"Rapid Response team members working to clear away the brush piles with loaders\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIuMjAxMi8wMy8wNy8yMl81Ml81Ml8zNzVfd29ya2luZ19jaGFvcy5qcGcGOgZFVFsIOgZwOgp0aHVtYkkiDTQ1MHg0NTA+BjsGVA/working_chaos.jpg\" height=\"300\" width=\"450\" /></p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"Order restored from chaos.\" title=\"Order restored from chaos.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbBlsHOgZmSSIsMjAxMi8wMy8wNy8yM18wMF8xMl83NDJfYWZ0ZXJfY2hhb3MuanBnBjoGRVQ/after_chaos.jpg\" height=\"370\" width=\"613\" /></p>\r\n<p>Please pray for the victims of this disaster, that they could feel the love of God, even though this devastating event took place in their lives. Also pray for our cleanup teams as they minister to these hurting people.</p>\r\n<p>If you would like to help CAM’s <a title=\"/programs/41\" href=\"/programs/41\">Rapid Response</a> teams assist needy victims of natural disasters across the USA, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to make a one-time donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>','2012-03-07 14:15:00','2012-03-07 14:18:46','2012-03-07 21:37:33',NULL,288,'News Release','This house in Marysville, IN blew from its foundation, landing 100 yards from its original location. Rapid Response team members are working at clearing away the debris.',41,'Rapid Response Disaster Service'),(45,'Providing alternate places of service','<p>Seventeen church groups across the United States have joined the <strong><a title=\"/programs/10\" href=\"/programs/10\">Conservative Anabaptist Service Program</a>\r\n</strong> (CASP) to prepare their youth in case of a draft. This program, organized under Christian Aid Ministries, has several projects in place where young men can volunteer, receive teaching on nonresistance, and experience life in a service environment. In 2011, more than 125 young men served in forestry, rebuilding, and international projects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The goal of <strong><a title=\"/programs/10\" href=\"/programs/10\">CASP</a>\r\n</strong> is to provide Selective Service System-approved places of employment with ethical and moral environments and that benefit our country’s health, safety, and other interests.</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 613px; height: 97px; font-weight: bold;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"font-size-large\">If you would like to help support this program, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to make a one-time donation using your credit card or bank account. Your donation will be used to cover the expenses of tools, food, lodging, and operations on CASP projects.</span>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','2012-03-01 17:00:00','2012-03-08 19:44:29','2012-03-23 19:19:53',NULL,296,'CAM Newsletter','Volunteers on a CASP forestry project in North Carolina.',10,'Conservative Anabaptist Service Program'),(46,'Dieuna\'s New Year','<p>Dieuna slowly woke up. “Dieuna, Dieuna, it is time for church!” That was her dad’s voice calling her, but how could it be time for church already? It was still pitch dark. Then it dawned on her. It was January 1!</p>\r\n<p>Dieuna (pronounced Jayna) and her family had done a lot of hard work to prepare for this day. They had moved all the furniture out of their house (in northwest Haiti) and had cleaned the house thoroughly from the tin roof and wooden rafters all the way down to the cement floor. Then they had carefully arranged their two lumpy beds, four chairs, small table, and wooden cabinet back in place again. Their house was going to look sparkly clean to welcome in the New Year. And now the New Year was finally here. What better way to welcome the New Year than by going to church at 3:00 a.m. to sing and pray to God as the sun rose over the horizon?</p>\r\n<p>It was a busy day. As soon as church was over, Dieuna’s mom needed her to help get wood for the fire and to fetch water from the spring to make their delicious pumpkin soup and coffee. After the soup was prepared, Dieuna’s mom dished most of it into a large serving bowl for their family and then separated the rest into four smaller containers for neighbors and family nearby.</p>\r\n<p>Just as she had hoped, Dieuna was sent over to her Uncle Samuel’s house, carrying a small container of pumpkin soup. That was Dieuna’s favorite job of all. Dieuna knew when she arrived at Uncle Samuel’s house, her aunt would give her a little treat—maybe sugared peanuts. Dieuna’s mouth watered just thinking about them.</p>\r\n<p>But wait! What was that noise? People were singing, but it wasn’t the songs Dieuna knew from church. Someone was beating on a drum. Now she could see them. The ladies had bright handkerchiefs tied on their heads. They were prancing around a tree. Oh! And there was a cow tied to the tree. The cow was pulling away from the tree, its neck stretched out. Dieuna wanted to laugh. It looked like the cow was singing, too, the way its neck was stretched out.  But soon she didn’t want to laugh anymore. People started to pick up rocks, and she realized they were going to throw them at the cow.</p>\r\n<p>Suddenly, returning home again seemed more important than eating sugared peanut treats. She didn’t stay long at Uncle Samuel’s house. As soon as she got home she asked her parents what was happening with the cow.</p>\r\n<p>Her dad explained to her, “Not everyone believes God can or will protect them, Dieuna. Some people think money is the best thing to have to protect them against problems. Some people think sacrificing cows, coffee, and money will protect them from bad things happening to them. That’s what the people you saw believe. Do you remember what I tell you if you are scared and need help or protection, Dieuna?”</p>\r\n<p>Dieuna grinned at her dad. How could she forget?  Almost every day her dad reminded her to trust in God when there were scary noises at night or other children would tell her scary stories. </p>\r\n<p>“Yes, Dad! I remember! ‘What time I am afraid, I will trust in thee.’ ”</p>\r\n<p>“That’s right, Dieuna! I hope you will never look anywhere except to God for what you need.”</p>','2012-03-01 18:00:00','2012-03-08 20:03:59','2012-03-23 19:19:45',NULL,297,'CAM Newsletter','Dieuna',NULL,'Children’s Corner'),(47,'Good seed from God\'s hand','<p>Oleg and Onya Yevdoshenko in Ukraine lost their house and all their belongings to a house fire in 2011. They provide for their family of four by operating a greenhouse with seeds they receive through CAM’s <strong><a title=\"/programs/24\" href=\"/programs/24\">Seed Project</a>\r\n</strong>. “With the financial situation we are in, these seeds provide much-needed sustenance for our growing family,” Onya said. “It is a great blessing for us since we lost our home.”</p>\r\n<p>To organize the <strong><a title=\"/programs/24\" href=\"/programs/24\">Seed Project</a>\r\n</strong> in Ukraine, CAM supplies high quality seeds, and Master’s International Ministries coordinates volunteers to package the bulk seeds into individual packets and family seed parcels. The parcels consist of eleven kinds of seeds and two Gospel tracts. Each January, volunteers from the United States, Canada, and local Ukrainian churches spend about six weeks packaging seeds, holding evangelistic meetings, and distributing seed parcels and Christian literature. The goal of the <strong><a title=\"/programs/24\" href=\"/programs/24\">Seed Project</a>\r\n</strong> is to point people to the Lord through the meetings and literature given with the seeds.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"Recipients can hardly believe their eyes when volunteers brave the cold Romanian weather to offer them good quality seeds. After receiving a pack of seeds and Christian literature, this woman exclaimed, “Praises be to the Lord!”\" title=\"Recipients can hardly believe their eyes when volunteers brave the cold Romanian weather to offer them good quality seeds. After receiving a pack of seeds and Christian literature, this woman exclaimed, “Praises be to the Lord!”\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIlMjAxMi8wMy8wOC8yM18xNl8zMV83NjJfU1BfMi5qcGcGOgZFVFsIOgZwOgp0aHVtYkkiDTQ1MHg0NTA+BjsGVA/SP_2.jpg\" height=\"450\" width=\"301\" /></p>\r\n<h3>Thanks from a seed recipient:</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">Dear brothers and sisters in Christ Jesus, I thank you very much for everything that was shared with us. I am fifty-two years old. My husband works only in winter as a stoker at the local school. We received a pack of seeds from you. We thank you and receive it as a gift from God’s hand! The seeds are very good quality. They have already sprouted! Our biggest income is what will grow in our garden this fall. Thank you, dear friends, for your kindness and mercy. With respect, Galina M. Kats’–Ukraine</p>\r\n<h3>Seeds for Liberian farmers</h3>\r\n<p>Liberian farmers yearn to put decades of violence behind them and unlock the rich potential of their soil. After the 1990s civil war, hundreds returned to their homes in the bush to find their crops destroyed and their land overgrown in thick brush. For the past several years, CAM\'s <strong><a title=\"/programs/24\" href=\"/programs/24\">Seed Project</a>\r\n</strong> has supplied some of these farmers with agricultural tools and seeds to rebuild their land. The gift of good quality seeds gives Liberians the resources to grow better crops and encourages them to become self-sustaining.</p>\r\n<p>For centuries, Liberians used the slash and burn method for farming, thus destroying their forests. We encourage them to grow rice in a swamp instead. They can reuse their land from one growing season to the next and be rewarded with good crops.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"Healthy plants from CAM seeds sprout in this Liberian’s carefully managed nursery.\" title=\"Healthy plants from CAM seeds sprout in this Liberian’s carefully managed nursery.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIlMjAxMi8wMy8wOC8yM18xNl8zMV84NTlfU1BfMy5qcGcGOgZFVFsIOgZwOgp0aHVtYkkiDTQ1MHg0NTA+BjsGVA/SP_3.jpg\" height=\"338\" width=\"450\" /></p>\r\n<p>Besides rice seed, we also provide some farmers with pepper, watermelon, bitter ball, okra, and cabbage seeds. The farmers plant these seeds in nurseries and then transplant them to the fields. </p>\r\n<p>Pastor Nelson, a national who coordinates the seed program in Liberia, visits the farmers to check their progress. He takes this opportunity to preach and distribute Bibles and Christian literature. Spiritual darkness and superstition grip many Liberians. Several villages had no Bibles in their native Bassa dialect, but after receiving Bibles from CAM, they began to hold Bible studies.</p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"width: 600px; border: 2px ridge #808080;\">\r\n	<p style=\"padding: 0px 6px 0px 6px;\">\r\n		If you would like to make a contribution to the 2012 Seed Project, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to make a one-time donation using your credit card or bank account. Each year, CAM provides tons of quality seeds to needy people in Ukraine, Liberia, Romania, Moldova, Nicaragua, and Haiti. Donations to this project cover the cost of seeds, garden tools, shipping and distribution.\r\n	</p>\r\n</div>','2012-03-01 19:00:00','2012-03-08 20:09:30','2012-03-23 19:19:35',NULL,298,'CAM Newsletter','Nicolai Horskiy and his wife are pleased with the seeds they receive from CAM. They share their extra crops with neighbors, which gives them an opportunity to talk about the Creator.',24,'Seed Project'),(48,'A bagful of joy','<p>An unusually harsh winter has settled over Eastern Europe, bringing with it subzero weather and piles of snow. Sadly, hundreds of people have lost their lives this winter due to the severe cold. Small children and the elderly are especially vulnerable to freezing temperatures. For those who cannot afford to adequately heat their houses, warm clothes and blankets are vital. But new clothing is expensive, and many families try to survive without sufficient coats or blankets. </p>\r\n<p>CAM’s contact in Moldova who distributes our donated clothing and comforters says, “There is still a great need for clothing in Moldova. A lot of poor families express joy and thankfulness [for donated clothing] because it’s impossible for them to buy new clothing.”</p>\r\n<p>The Robert Lupu family in Suceava, Romania, lives in an area with very few fellow Christians. Robert tries to earn a living with his honeybees during the summer, but the family does not have a source of income in the winter months. Imagine their joy when the CAM delivery truck stops at their house. Nicu Tcaciuc, the driver, hops down and opens the back door of the truck. From the house, the Lupu children press their faces against the windowpane and watch as Nicu hands a white sack of clothing to their father. Robert carries the bundle inside, a huge grin on his worn face. His wife and children eagerly open the bag and pull out sweaters, dresses, pants, shirts, shoes, coats, and boots. They praise God for providing for their needs with this precious bag of clothing.</p>\r\n<p>Echoing the Lupu family’s gratefulness, another recipient writes, <em>My words can\'t express my thanks for all you do for us, but my heart is bursting with joy and I thank you for everything . . . We even fix the clothes that are too loose or big. Our sister is a seamstress, and she makes that we all have something to wear from old to young and then we hand them down as well.</em>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Generous individuals and churches have donated millions of pounds of clothing, footwear, and thousands of warm comforters to CAM. Your gift helps ship these items to Eastern Europe and some other countries for people who need them most. </p>\r\n<div style=\"width: 600px; border: 2px ridge #808080;\">\r\n	<p style=\"padding: 0px 6px 0px 6px;\">\r\nIf you would like to help bring joy by providing a clothing bundle, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account. For every $69, we can ship and distribute 155 pounds of clothing, footwear, and comforters.\r\n</p>\r\n</div>','2012-03-01 21:14:00','2012-03-16 20:17:19','2012-04-04 17:23:37',NULL,314,'CAM Newsletter','Will something fit me? The Lupu children excitedly reach into the clothing bag their family just received.',9,'Clothing Bundle Project'),(49,'A brighter future','<p>Imagine sitting at your window and watching the world hustle by, while you can move only with great effort. You have tried to walk a number of times, but the falls you take are painful and deeply discourage you. The handicap you face every day prevents you from doing many ordinary tasks. If you had something as simple as a walker or wheelchair, your life might have a brighter future.</p>\r\n<p>Seven-year-old Hamzi in the southern Judean mountains of Israel cannot walk or talk like most boys his age. His eleven-year-old sister Hanan suffers from the same birth defect, though she can communicate and walk with support. Their family struggles to make ends meet. Recently, through CAM’s <strong><a title=\"/programs/42\" href=\"/programs/42\">Hope-for-the-Handicapped</a>\r\n</strong> (HFTH) program, both children received a walker, a crucial instrument in improving their motor skills and development. As Hamzi slowly stepped behind his new walker, the smile on his face radiated the happiness he felt. </p>\r\n<p>George Aboyacob, in a West Bank village, had both legs amputated above the knees due to gangrene. His wheelchair was repaired by CAM, and his motorized buggy refurbished and a new battery installed. Through the <strong><a title=\"/programs/42\" href=\"/programs/42\">HFTH</a>\r\n</strong> program, many recipients in Israel and other countries receive the care and attention they need, be it through a wheelchair, walker, food, medical supplies, or other items.</p>\r\n<p>In many countries, handicapped children and adults are neglected or abandoned by their families or live in facilities too poor to give sufficient supplies and care. After seeing hundreds of suffering, disabled people, many in pitiable conditions, CAM started the <strong><a title=\"/programs/42\" href=\"/programs/42\">Hope-for-the-Handicapped</a>\r\n</strong>\r\n<span> program to help meet the unique needs of these people. Through the generosity of sponsors, they not only receive physical support, but also experience the love of God in a real way.</span>\r\n</p>\r\n<div style=\"width: 600px; border: 2px ridge #808080;\">\r\n	<p style=\"padding: 0px 6px 0px 6px;\">\r\nTo help provide wheelchairs, medical supplies, food, or other care for handicapped people in Israel, Liberia, Haiti, and other countries, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n','2012-03-01 22:12:00','2012-03-19 18:17:25','2012-04-04 17:23:22',NULL,318,'CAM Newsletter','In Israel, Hamzi smiles from behind the walker he received from CAM.',42,'Hope-for-the-Handicapped'),(50,'Helping families support themselves','<p>Bogdan Beda, in western Ukraine, is a busy man, pastoring a church and working hard to support his growing family. Raising two and a half acres of potatoes used to be extremely difficult for Bogdan and his wife Nastya. All the work, such as bug control and weeding, needed to be done by hand. Bogdan dreamed of someday owning a tractor. </p>\r\n<p>Unfortunately, as fast as he saved money for a tractor, the price of the tractor went up. It seemed his dream would never come true. But then God answered Bogdan’s prayers through CAM’s <strong><a title=\"/programs/12\" href=\"/programs/12\">Family-Self-Support</a>\r\n</strong> (FSS) program. Donations from sponsors helped him buy the tractor he needed. Now he is better able to meet the needs of his family and have more time to spend with them.</p>\r\n<p>The goal of <strong><a title=\"/programs/12\" href=\"/programs/12\">Family-Self-Support</a>\r\n</strong> is to help needy families come to the point where they can support themselves rather than rely on material aid. The program operates in Romania, Moldova, Ukraine, Israel, Haiti, Liberia, and Kenya. Sponsors provide funds for families to buy tools, machinery, land, greenhouses, animals, or other resources to make a living. </p>\r\n<p>Zhenia Zavalokiye in Ukraine grew up at an orphanage. Born with some physical disabilities, it didn’t seem he would have many opportunities to succeed in life. Today, with tools purchased through <strong><a title=\"/programs/12\" href=\"/programs/12\">FSS</a>\r\n</strong>, he does heating, plumbing, and electrical service work. Zhenia is now able to keep his six little ones fed and clothed. His children often pray for their brothers and sisters in Christ who donated the money. </p>\r\n<p>It took Sergey some time to figure out just how he was going to build the new greenhouse he received from CAM through the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/12\" href=\"/programs/12\">FSS</a> program. “But once we got started,” he says, “my children were just as anxious as I to get it finished. Our greenhouse provides work for all ages, whether it is keeping firewood in the boiler twenty-four hours a day, keeping the young, tender plants warm, or the backbreaking job of weeding and transplanting. The joys of the harvest make it worth all the work and worry.”</p>\r\n<div style=\"width: 600px; border: 2px ridge #808080;\">\r\n            <p style=\"padding: 0px 6px 0px 6px;\">\r\nIf you would like to help provide resources for needy families to make a living, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>\r\n</div>','2012-03-01 23:07:00','2012-03-23 19:11:59','2012-04-04 17:23:07',NULL,324,'CAM Newsletter','Bogdan spraying his potato fields with the tractor he purchased through Family-Self-Support.',12,'Family-Self-Support'),(51,'Gifts that give hope','<p>Bendu Maldeh, from Kandea, Liberia, lives with her only son Eddie in a mud hut in their village. When she heard the good news that CAM was distributing food parcels for widows at her church, she quickly made her way there, hoping to receive a parcel. Overjoyed to take home a parcel, Bendu said, “Thank you, and God bless you!”</p>\r\n<p>Sponsors of the <a style=\"font-weight: bold;\" title=\"/programs/28\" href=\"/programs/28\">Support-A-Widow</a> program make it possible to provide food parcels to thousands of needy widows, widowers, and abandoned wives in Liberia, Haiti, Romania, Nicaragua, and other countries. Each thirty-five-pound parcel contains rice, beans, cooking oil, soap, and other food and healthcare items, along with a Seed of Truth magazine and $10 cash. To us these gifts may not seem like much, but to widows in desperate poverty, they are a big help and relief!</p>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div style=\"width: 600px; border: 2px ridge #808080;\">\r\n            <p style=\"padding: 0px 6px 0px 6px;\">\r\nWould you like to bring a bit of sunshine and hope to needy widows, widowers, and abandoned wives in Haiti, Romania, Liberia, Nicaragua, Moldova, Ukraine, or Israel? Use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>\r\n</div>','2012-03-02 02:14:00','2012-03-23 19:16:19','2012-03-23 19:17:57',NULL,325,'News Release','Bendu Maldeh praises God for the Support-A-Widow parcel she received.',28,'Support-A-Widow'),(52,'A bundle can save a baby’s life','<p>by Gloria Miller, CAM secretary in Liberia</p>\r\n<ul style=\"font-style: italic;\"><li>For every 100 babies born in Liberia, 7 die.</li>\r\n<li>Of the 172 countries in the world, Liberia ranks fifth for maternal deaths. </li>\r\n<li>In Liberia, 1 in 20 women die in childbirth, while in America, only 1 in 2,100 die. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>And now, stepping from statistics into reality.</p>\r\n<h3>Grand Bassa County; Liberia, West Africa</h3>\r\n<p>Today I am in the heart of Grand Bassa County at the CAM-sponsored clinic in Jacob Larety Town. They tell me this county rates the highest in all of Liberia for childbirth deaths. </p>\r\n<p>The Jacob Larety Town clinic serves eighty-six surrounding villages. Even in this modern age of 2012, we can’t drive a car to the clinic. We take a car from the nearest town to the river, which we cross in a dugout canoe and then hike five minutes to the clinic. </p>\r\n<p>Under a thatch roofed hut outside the clinic, I hold babies and talk to Tamba, the clinic director. He tells me how mothers—and often their babies—die because they don’t have access to medical care, and their attendants (traditional midwives) are ill-trained to deal with complications. Many of these deaths are preventable, such as obstructed labor, hemorrhaging, and postpartum sepsis, and could be averted if the women would only come to Tamba’s clinic to have their babies.</p>\r\n<p>But distance and culture keeps many women from coming to the clinic to have their babies. Traditional midwives pressure women to have their babies in the villages and to pay the midwives to assist them in delivery. These women agree, because it has always been done this way. But the traditional midwives often use obsolete and atrocious practices, and sometimes things go wrong. Tamba heard how one midwife blew cigarette smoke into a baby’s mouth and nose to try to get it to breathe.</p>\r\n<p>In the two and a half years Tamba has been practicing at the clinic, he has heard of seven childbirth deaths in the nearby area. Most of these deaths could have been prevented, had the women come to his clinic instead of going to the midwife in their village.</p>\r\n<p>So Tamba has an idea—an incentive for women to come to his clinic to have their babies. His incentive is something simple. Something you in America give. Baby bundles.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"/news/layette-bundles\" title=\"Layette Bundles\"><img src=\"/system/images/BAhbBlsHOgZmSSIkMjAxMi8wMy8yOS8yMV8wMF8zOV81NzdfYmIzLmpwZwY6BkVU/bb3.jpg\" height=\"360\" width=\"576\" /></a>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>These bundles contain blankets, diapers, pins, socks, sleepers, and baby caps. Sounds simple, but to these Liberian women, it’s so special they just might break tradition and make the extra effort to come to the clinic to have their baby.</p>\r\n<p>If the mothers come to the Jacob Larety Town clinic, they have a chance. A chance to live, and if they run into any problems, they are only five minutes from the river, where there is a canoe and a taxi on the other side to take them to the nearest hospital. </p>\r\n<p>While at Jacob Larety Town clinic, we met two women who received a bundle from Tamba, because they made the effort to come to the clinic to have their babies. </p>\r\n<p>Moima was on her way to the clinic, from deep in the bush and didn’t quite make it to the clinic but delivered her baby on the way. Because of the effort she applied, Tamba still gave her a bundle. Nancy, another mother, was thrilled with her baby bundle. Her little Kulah Angel, a chubby healthy baby, was born just two and a half weeks before we visited the clinic. They let Nancy choose her bundle, and she chose a pink one. </p>\r\n<p>A baby bundle. Something small, but not insignificant. Because it might help save the lives of a mother and her baby.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"Staff members at Jacob Larety Town clinic say if it were not for their monthly supply of CAM-donated medicines and other supplies, there is no way they could stay in operation.\" title=\"Staff members at Jacob Larety Town clinic say if it were not for their monthly supply of CAM-donated medicines and other supplies, there is no way they could stay in operation.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSImMjAxMi8wNC8wMi8xOF80OF8zMV81NDFfR1RHXzIuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg00NTB4NDUwPgY7BlQ/GTG_2.jpg\" height=\"450\" width=\"441\" /></p>\r\n<h3><a title=\"/programs/13\" href=\"/programs/13\">Gifts-That-Grow</a>\r\n</h3>\r\n<p>Mothers who come to the Jacob Larety Town clinic also receive CAM-donated prenatal vitamins. Thanks to CAM’s<strong> <a title=\"/programs/13\" href=\"/programs/13\">Gifts-That-Grow</a>\r\n</strong> program, thousands of dollars’ worth of medicines and vitamins are shipped to Liberia, including Kirk’s prenatal vitamins. Tamba says these vitamins are so valuable, they cannot even be found at the large government hospitals. In this country with such a high childbirth death rate, a product containing vitamins A, B, C, D, and K are priceless. These vitamins also contain Iodine and Iron, which are so important for a mother’s health before and after the birth of her baby. </p>\r\n<p>CAM also ships a Child Health and Growth vitamin, which greatly improves the health of little children here in Liberia. But vitamins are only a small part of the <strong><a title=\"/programs/13\" href=\"/programs/13\">Gifts-That-Grow</a>\r\n</strong> program in Liberia. We receive hundreds of medicines as well, and we see them make a life-changing difference for hundreds of people at CAM-sponsored clinics.</p>\r\n<div style=\"width: 600px; border: 2px ridge #808080;\">\r\n            <p style=\"padding: 0px 6px 0px 6px;\">\r\nWould you like to help procure and ship free products for the poor in Liberia and other countries? Please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account.</p> </div>','2012-03-26 16:00:00','2012-03-29 15:28:13','2012-04-02 14:50:28',NULL,327,'News Release','Little Kulah Angel’s mother chose a pink baby bundle.',13,'Gifts-That-Grow'),(53,'Layette Bundles','<h3>Thousands of bundles could be used!</h3>\r\n<h4>Please use only NEW items for these bundles!</h4>\r\n<p>2 -  blankets (1 receiving and 1 heavier one) <br />6 - diapers (absorbent 100% cotton or flannel, long preferred—not pre-folded or square ones) <br />2 - sleepers (1 small, 1 medium)<br />2 - rubber panties      <br />2 - undershirts or onesies<br />2 - pairs socks or booties<br />1 - baby cap<br />4 - diaper pins</p>\r\n<p>Wrap all items in one of the blankets and fasten with the diaper pins (or tie together with ribbon, since diaper pins tend to get rusty in some countries). May be labeled “boy” or “girl.”</p>\r\n<p>Important: Because of customs declarations, we request that you stay with the items listed above. <strong>All items must be new. </strong>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Put all the kits into a large box or bag. Label each box/ bag with the amount of kits inside. The kits can be dropped off at any CAM location, or mailed to our warehouse in PA. (Attn: Shipping Department; Christian Aid Ministries, 2412 Division Highway; Ephrata, PA 17522-9310; Phone: 717-354-2434). </p>\r\n<p>In a separate envelope, please send $2.50 per bundle to the Ohio office (PO Box 360, Berlin, OH 44610) for shipping and distribution costs. </p>\r\n<p>The kits will be shipped by sea container to the countries of Nicaragua, Haiti, Liberia, Romania, or the former Soviet Union, and given to needy people.</p>','2012-03-26 15:00:00','2012-03-29 15:30:23','2012-03-29 15:35:50',NULL,328,'CAM Newsletter','',NULL,''),(54,'A brighter future for Romania’s Gypsy children','<p>Simona Rusu, a young Gypsy girl, in Suceava, Romania, suffers from a heart defect and needs to be on medication. Her father struggles to find work due to health problems, and their only regular source of income is $13 a month from the state. Life didn’t hold much hope for Simona, but then she had the opportunity to go to a <strong><a title=\"/programs/18\" href=\"/programs/18\">Jericho Road Ministries</a>\r\n</strong> remedial school. Saveta, her teacher, is assisting her mostly in math and language. Today, Simona aspires to finish school, find a job, and help the poor. </p>\r\n<p>CAM’s <strong><a title=\"/programs/18\" href=\"/programs/18\">Jericho Road Ministries</a>\r\n</strong> (JRM) operates four remedial schools in Suceava, Romania, for underprivileged Gypsy children and youth. JRM also translates and distributes Christian literature and gives seeds, food, and other aid to needy Gyspy families, elderly people, widows, and orphans. </p>\r\n<h3>Does <a title=\"/programs/18\" href=\"/programs/18\">Jericho Road Ministries</a> make a difference?</h3>\r\n<p>A Christian father in the village of Patrauti, Romania, commented how the behavior of the children has improved in this section of town since the remedial school has been there. The children are not uncivilized and wild as before. Good, positive, Bible-based teaching does make a difference!</p>\r\n<p>Please pray for Simona and the many other Gypsy children in Romania who have a dark history, but with your help, and the grace of God, can expect a brighter future. </p>\r\n<div style=\"width: 600px; border: 2px ridge #808080;\">\r\n	<p style=\"padding: 0px 6px 0px 6px;\">\r\nTo help Gypsy children learn to read and write, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to make a one-time donation using your credit card or bank account.</p>\r\n</div>','2012-03-26 17:00:00','2012-04-04 17:06:23','2012-04-04 17:06:23',NULL,335,'News Release','Simona',18,'Jericho Road Ministries'),(55,'In search of the Bible way','<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">A Paraguayan man’s search for a church that practices the doctrines taught in the Bible.</p>\r\n<p>Soon after Mario committed his life to Christ at age twenty-one, he traveled to his home village, Villarica, Paraguay, and preached the Gospel to family and friends. After several months, he moved to Vya-Renda and helped start a church. One day, an unbeliever passing through Vya-Renda sarcastically gave a <em>La Antorcha de la Verdad</em> (The Torch of Truth) magazine to an elderly Christian woman in the village. After reading the magazine, she passed it on to Mario. In the next two years, they acquired more issues of the magazine. </p>\r\n<p>The members at the small church in Vya-Renda were deeply impacted by the Biblical teachings they discovered in the <em>Antorcha</em> magazine. They decided to  follow its teachings and developed seven articles as guidelines. These included work, business, clothing, music, sports, and more. They decided tobacco, a common crop in their area, is not for the Christian. In the non-resistance article they decided to not own guns or buy firecrackers. They also decided to not use instrumental music for worship. From an article in the <em>Antorcha</em> on providing for our own, and the examples given on how to raise funds, they went to work and soon had enough funds to build a church house.</p>\r\n<p>For nine years, the church worked happily together. Then a new family moved to Vya-Renda. They agreed to the church guidelines and became members, but soon began to sow discord and doubts. About the same time, a local evangelist convinced the church to have revival meetings with loud music and “tremendous preaching.” When the evangelist ran off with a young girl from the church, Mario decided to take his family out of Vya-Renda.</p>\r\n<p>After leaving Vya-Renda, Mario wrote Publicadora La Merced (PLM), the conservative Mennonite publisher of <em>Antorcha</em>, to see if there were any churches in Paraguay that practice the doctrines taught in the magazine. A few months later, he received a letter from PLM with the name and address of a minister at the Luz y Esperanza Amish Mennonite church. But when he took the address to the main post office in the capital, they could not help him locate the church.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"450x450\" alt=\"The letter Mario received from Publicadora La Merced.\" title=\"The letter Mario received from Publicadora La Merced.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSImMjAxMi8wNC8wNC8yMV8xNV8wNl8xNDJfQ0ZNXzIuanBnBjoGRVRbCDoGcDoKdGh1bWJJIg00NTB4NDUwPgY7BlQ/CFM_2.jpg\" height=\"351\" width=\"450\" /></p>\r\n<p>A year passed. Then Mario met a man named Michael who was also receiving the <em>Antorcha</em>, and he asked Michael to help him find the Luz y Esperanza church. Michael found a phone number, and Mario called the bishop of the church. He was amazed to find a native pastor in a church that practices the teachings of the <em>Antorcha</em>. Immediately plans were made for Mario to visit. </p>\r\n<p><img class=\"add-caption\" rel=\"225x255\" alt=\"A copy of the Antorcha.\" title=\"A copy of the Antorcha.\" src=\"/system/images/BAhbB1sHOgZmSSIoMjAxMi8wNC8wNC8yMV8xNV8wNl8yM19hbnRvcmNoYS5qcGcGOgZFVFsIOgZwOgp0aHVtYkkiDTIyNXgyNTU+BjsGVA/antorcha.jpg\" height=\"255\" width=\"166\" /></p>\r\n<p>A house and work became available for Mario and his family, and December 21, 2011, found them moving to the La Belleza area, all their possessions on the back of a pickup truck. Joy overflowed from their hearts onto their faces. After all these years, they had finally located a church that practices the Bible way.</p>\r\n<div style=\"width: 600px; border: 2px ridge #808080;\">\r\n	<p style=\"padding: 0px 6px 0px 6px;\">\r\nIf you would like to help provide Christian family magazines in places where sound, Biblical teaching is scarce, please use the “Donate Now” button below. You will be able to select either a one-time or monthly recurring donation using your credit card or bank account. $50 prints, ships, and distributes 125 copies of<em> La Antorcha de la Verdad</em> or <em>The Seed of Truth</em> Christian family magazines.  </p>\r\n</div>','2012-03-26 18:00:00','2012-04-04 17:16:55','2012-04-04 17:20:10',NULL,337,'News Release','Mario with his wife Nidia and their five children.',3,'Christian Family Magazines'),(56,'Schedule of Events – April & May','<h2>Oregon presentations</h2>\r\n<h3>CAM Open House slides</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\">See and hear the slide presentation shared by our field staff at the 2011 CAM Open House.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Tuesday, May 1, 2012 - 7 p.m.</strong>\r\n<br />Halsey Mennonite Church<br />910 E. First Street<br />Halsey, OR 97348<br />Contact: Darrel Hostetler - 541-401-2838</p>\r\n<p><strong>Friday, May 4, 2012 - 7:30 p.m.</strong>\r\n<br />Elliott Prairie Christian School<br />5383 S. Schneider Rd.<br />Woodburn, OR  97071<br />Contact: Jake Kropf - 541-466-5911</p>\r\n<p><strong>Saturday, May 5, 2012 - 7:00 p.m.</strong>\r\n<br />Western Interlock Training Center<br />10395 Rickreall Rd.<br />Rickreall, OR 97371<br />Contact: Rich Moore - 503-930-9888</p>\r\n<p><strong>Sunday, May 6, 2012 - 6:00 p.m.</strong>\r\n<br />Garfield Grange<br />33460 SE Divers Road<br />Estacada, OR 97023<br />Contact: Nolan Bechtel - 503-539-7354</p>','2012-04-04 17:54:00','2012-04-04 17:55:46','2012-04-05 13:01:03',NULL,NULL,'CAM Newsletter','',NULL,'');
